1
00:00:47,614 --> 00:00:52,618
     -A comic strip, to me,
           is a story

2
00:00:52,620 --> 00:00:55,687
     And a real brief story.

3
00:00:55,689 --> 00:00:58,290
It's like having the opportunity

4
00:00:58,292 --> 00:01:03,629
          To get a peek
 into people, characters' lives.

5
00:01:03,631 --> 00:01:07,800
  And they can make you laugh.
     They can make you cry.

6
00:01:07,802 --> 00:01:11,070
They just have an impact on you.

7
00:01:11,072 --> 00:01:15,507
 For the time that you read it,
    it's a world unto itself.

8
00:01:29,122 --> 00:01:31,590
    -My mom was always trying
       to get me to read,

9
00:01:31,592 --> 00:01:36,395
 And I wasn't really into books
   with "words," so to speak.

10
00:01:36,397 --> 00:01:39,098
  -My dad brought home a couple
  of "calvin and hobbes" books.

11
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:42,701
  -And he showed me some comic
 strips of "calvin and hobbes,"

12
00:01:42,703 --> 00:01:44,470
     And I was like, "whoa!"

13
00:01:44,472 --> 00:01:46,839
       -And I can remember
         opening it up,

14
00:01:46,841 --> 00:01:50,442
  I turned the page, and hobbes
     wanted me to have this.

15
00:01:50,444 --> 00:01:53,545
     And from that point on,
 it was me, calvin, and hobbes.

16
00:01:53,547 --> 00:01:56,815
    -I met calvin and hobbes
    in the paper, I think,
    the way most people did.

17
00:01:56,817 --> 00:01:58,584
  -Looking through the comics,

18
00:01:58,586 --> 00:02:00,619
     And "calvin and hobbes"
 was always one that stood out.

19
00:02:00,621 --> 00:02:03,155
  -My grandmother is a huge fan
     of "calvin and hobbes."

20
00:02:03,157 --> 00:02:06,492
   -My first and only crime --
     I shoplifted this book.

21
00:02:06,494 --> 00:02:08,193
          [ chuckles ]

22
00:02:08,195 --> 00:02:10,896
     -And I found this book
of "complete calvin and hobbes."

23
00:02:10,898 --> 00:02:13,866
       It was in english,
   but I said, "I don't care.

24
00:02:13,868 --> 00:02:17,202
 I'm gonna learn this language
 just to understand this book."

25
00:02:17,204 --> 00:02:18,470
       -I was babysitting,

26
00:02:18,472 --> 00:02:20,739
    And a couple of the kids
         that I babysat,

27
00:02:20,741 --> 00:02:22,141
      They had some books.

28
00:02:22,143 --> 00:02:23,542
 -All the books got passed to me

29
00:02:23,544 --> 00:02:25,444
     And ended up in my room
           for awhile.

30
00:02:25,446 --> 00:02:27,679
 You know, we'd be trading them
         back and forth.

31
00:02:27,681 --> 00:02:29,214
-I hadn't seen the strip before,

32
00:02:29,216 --> 00:02:31,183
       But I saw the book
         in a bookstore.

33
00:02:31,185 --> 00:02:33,152
-And it was on sale. It was like
   $3 or something like that.

34
00:02:33,154 --> 00:02:34,786
   So I was like, "all right.
        I'll look at it."

35
00:02:34,788 --> 00:02:37,756
  Pulled it open, and the first
  thing I saw was the snowmen.

36
00:02:37,758 --> 00:02:39,391
    -And I burst out laughing

37
00:02:39,393 --> 00:02:41,760
 And proceeded to get in trouble
        in english class.

38
00:02:41,762 --> 00:02:44,663
  -I remember just reading that
  thing over and over and over.

39
00:02:44,665 --> 00:02:48,367
    -Even now, I reread them,
 and I continue to reread them.

40
00:02:48,369 --> 00:02:53,372
 I discover so many layers now,
 and it's never boring or old.

41
00:02:53,374 --> 00:02:54,806
 It's just like a living thing,

42
00:02:54,808 --> 00:02:56,675
     And I just discover it
     and appreciate it more.

43
00:02:56,677 --> 00:02:58,810
     -Calvin is like the kid
    you want to be, you know?

44
00:02:58,812 --> 00:03:01,280
             Even if
  you're a 300-pound black kid,

45
00:03:01,282 --> 00:03:03,549
             I mean,
  you still want to be calvin.

46
00:03:05,752 --> 00:03:08,420
    -I   <i>di</i>want to be calvin.

47
00:03:08,422 --> 00:03:10,889
    I felt like I <i>was</i> calvin.

48
00:03:10,891 --> 00:03:13,892
   We were both six years old
            in 1985.

49
00:03:13,894 --> 00:03:17,563
     We liked tigers, space,
      playing in the snow,

50
00:03:17,565 --> 00:03:20,199
           Had fathers
  who loved building character,

51
00:03:20,201 --> 00:03:21,767
  And I took pride in the fact

52
00:03:21,769 --> 00:03:24,670
     That my first hairstyle
     was quite calvin-esque.

53
00:03:24,672 --> 00:03:27,472
        But the truth is
  that I don't really remember

54
00:03:27,474 --> 00:03:29,575
        When I first met
       calvin and hobbes.

55
00:03:29,577 --> 00:03:32,277
I'd like to think I was a reader
          from day one,

56
00:03:32,279 --> 00:03:34,213
 But I know that isn't possible.

57
00:03:34,215 --> 00:03:36,782
  My hometown newspaper didn't
  even start carrying the strip

58
00:03:36,784 --> 00:03:39,218
      Until spring of 1988.

59
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:41,787
       The earliest memory
  that I can stamp with a date

60
00:03:41,789 --> 00:03:44,489
      Would be third grade
   in mrs. Smith's classroom,

61
00:03:44,491 --> 00:03:46,825
           When I saw
a "calvin and hobbes" collection

62
00:03:46,827 --> 00:03:48,594
 In the scholastic book catalog.

63
00:03:48,596 --> 00:03:50,462
   But if I examine my books,

64
00:03:50,464 --> 00:03:53,332
    I find that the only one
     with a scholastic logo

65
00:03:53,334 --> 00:03:55,634
     Is "scientific progress
         goes 'boink,'"

66
00:03:55,636 --> 00:03:58,670
    With a copyright of 1991.

67
00:03:58,672 --> 00:04:01,306
      If I didn't discover
      "calvin and hobbes"

68
00:04:01,308 --> 00:04:04,343
    Until that late in life,
    I'm secretly embarrassed.

69
00:04:04,345 --> 00:04:06,545
        And I would also
        blame my parents.

70
00:04:06,547 --> 00:04:09,948
        -That little boy
     seemed kind of naughty,

71
00:04:09,950 --> 00:04:11,817
        And I didn't know

72
00:04:11,819 --> 00:04:16,855
  If I wanted my son interested
  in a naughty comic character.

73
00:04:16,857 --> 00:04:19,524
          -Apparently,
      no thanks to my mom,

74
00:04:19,526 --> 00:04:22,594
        Calvin and hobbes
     were just always there,

75
00:04:22,596 --> 00:04:25,964
And I don't really remember life
          without them.

76
00:04:29,602 --> 00:04:32,571
 I may have fallen in love with
 "calvin and hobbes" as a kid,

77
00:04:32,573 --> 00:04:34,439
         But it's one of
        those rare things

78
00:04:34,441 --> 00:04:37,376
     That still holds great
 significance to me as an adult.

79
00:04:37,378 --> 00:04:40,379
     I really can't think of
 anything else from my childhood

80
00:04:40,381 --> 00:04:42,547
That has retained so much value.

81
00:04:42,549 --> 00:04:45,617
  I don't claim to be an expert
          on comics --

82
00:04:45,619 --> 00:04:46,818
       I'm not even close.

83
00:04:46,820 --> 00:04:48,620
    I never read comic books,

84
00:04:48,622 --> 00:04:51,757
  I haven't read the newspaper
  comics regularly for years,

85
00:04:51,759 --> 00:04:54,593
 And I've only recently started
      to reacquaint myself

86
00:04:54,595 --> 00:04:57,396
      With what the comics
       have to offer now.

87
00:04:57,398 --> 00:05:00,999
But for years, I read and reread
  my "calvin and hobbes" books,

88
00:05:01,001 --> 00:05:04,036
          Which always
     put a smile on my face.

89
00:05:04,038 --> 00:05:05,904
          And the strip
       still holds meaning

90
00:05:05,906 --> 00:05:08,340
    For so many other readers
        around the world.

91
00:05:08,342 --> 00:05:10,542
             I know
  because I've heard from them,

92
00:05:10,544 --> 00:05:12,644
       And they've sent me
         their stories.

93
00:05:12,646 --> 00:05:15,781
     Many people have tried
  to track down bill watterson

94
00:05:15,783 --> 00:05:17,349
         Over the years.

95
00:05:17,351 --> 00:05:19,918
    But I'm not so interested
       in the man himself

96
00:05:19,920 --> 00:05:23,322
 But why his simple comic strip
    about a boy and his tiger

97
00:05:23,324 --> 00:05:25,490
 Could somehow have such meaning

98
00:05:25,492 --> 00:05:29,027
  And have had such a personal
    impact on so many people.

99
00:05:29,029 --> 00:05:31,630
         Just as people
    often find it a challenge

100
00:05:31,632 --> 00:05:33,865
  To describe the strip itself,

101
00:05:33,867 --> 00:05:35,867
             I think
 anybody would have a hard time

102
00:05:35,869 --> 00:05:38,503
   Distilling the ingredients
    that made it what it is.

103
00:05:38,505 --> 00:05:40,906
       But we can be sure
         of one thing --

104
00:05:40,908 --> 00:05:43,575
      On November 18, 1985,

105
00:05:43,577 --> 00:05:45,811
    Bill watterson's creation
             debuted

106
00:05:45,813 --> 00:05:47,813
 In just a few dozen newspapers,

107
00:05:47,815 --> 00:05:50,749
 And it left an enormous imprint
      on countless readers

108
00:05:50,751 --> 00:05:53,051
     From across the globe.

109
00:05:55,988 --> 00:05:59,024
      -Well, the very first
  "calvin and hobbes" strip --

110
00:05:59,026 --> 00:06:01,927
           Calvin off
     to check his tiger trap

111
00:06:01,929 --> 00:06:04,730
        That he rigged up
   with a tuna fish sandwich,

112
00:06:04,732 --> 00:06:07,532
        And sure enough,
       in the last frame,

113
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:10,702
       We see that hobbes
    has fallen for the bait,

114
00:06:10,704 --> 00:06:14,873
     And he has his very own
     tiger friend for life.

115
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:18,977
      And that is our intro
     to "calvin and hobbes."

116
00:06:18,979 --> 00:06:20,379
     -I've never met anyone

117
00:06:20,381 --> 00:06:22,114
        Who doesn't like
      "calvin and hobbes."

118
00:06:22,116 --> 00:06:24,516
      So, I can't say that
     about any other strip.

119
00:06:24,518 --> 00:06:26,618
   And there are other strips
  that are very, very popular,

120
00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:27,819
        Very successful.

121
00:06:27,821 --> 00:06:29,154
     Most people love them,

122
00:06:29,156 --> 00:06:31,490
        But, invariably,
I'll run into someone that says,

123
00:06:31,492 --> 00:06:32,858
 "I just don't get that strip,"

124
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:34,793
    Or, "I really don't like
          that strip."

125
00:06:34,795 --> 00:06:37,028
    With "calvin and hobbes,"
         it's different.

126
00:06:37,030 --> 00:06:39,931
   It just seems to appeal to
   all different audiences --

127
00:06:39,933 --> 00:06:41,633
 Young and old and men and women

128
00:06:41,635 --> 00:06:44,136
   And people in the country,
       people in the city.

129
00:06:44,138 --> 00:06:46,471
         I mean, really,
     just all demographics.

130
00:06:46,473 --> 00:06:48,874
  It seems to speak to people.

131
00:06:48,876 --> 00:06:51,777
 -Everyone, you know, is united
 by their love for this strip,

132
00:06:51,779 --> 00:06:54,579
   But everyone has a specific
  thing that they love about it

133
00:06:54,581 --> 00:06:56,715
       Or specific things
    that they love about it.

134
00:06:56,717 --> 00:06:58,183
          And it's not
     always the same thing.

135
00:06:58,185 --> 00:07:00,652
        -Well, I grew up
   in a mexican neighborhood.

136
00:07:00,654 --> 00:07:03,422
   I went to a white school,
   and I was like 300 pounds,

137
00:07:03,424 --> 00:07:05,757
   So I didn't really fit in,
     but neither did calvin,

138
00:07:05,759 --> 00:07:07,993
           And, like,
   it wasn't really a problem.

139
00:07:07,995 --> 00:07:10,162
    He was just, "I'm weird,
    and that's the way I am,

140
00:07:10,164 --> 00:07:11,830
       And that's the way
         I'm gonna be."

141
00:07:11,832 --> 00:07:13,665
           And I think
    that's one of the things

142
00:07:13,667 --> 00:07:15,967
That really kind of attracted me
        to the character.

143
00:07:15,969 --> 00:07:17,469
  -What really resonated to me

144
00:07:17,471 --> 00:07:19,204
Was the whole imagination aspect
              of it

145
00:07:19,206 --> 00:07:21,573
   And how he just created it
          in his head,

146
00:07:21,575 --> 00:07:23,742
     And he didn't even see
  his teacher or his principal.

147
00:07:23,744 --> 00:07:26,745
     He just saw saw aliens,
   and he was spaceman spiff.

148
00:07:26,747 --> 00:07:29,581
       -It's a very deep,
  very philosophical experience

149
00:07:29,583 --> 00:07:31,683
             Reading
   a "calvin and hobbes" book,

150
00:07:31,685 --> 00:07:33,919
  Even though, on the surface,
     they're just cartoons.

151
00:07:33,921 --> 00:07:37,122
 -He's really created characters
         that, I think,

152
00:07:37,124 --> 00:07:40,926
     Have a lot of depth and
 are interesting to read about.

153
00:07:40,928 --> 00:07:44,062
      -"calvin and hobbes"
   is such a subversive comic.

154
00:07:44,064 --> 00:07:47,666
    But it has a purity to it
     that most comics don't,

155
00:07:47,668 --> 00:07:49,000
     Because it is so joyful

156
00:07:49,002 --> 00:07:51,570
And very much in the imagination
          of this kid,

157
00:07:51,572 --> 00:07:54,639
    And yet he is hyperaware
         of world events

158
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:57,909
   And pop culture and ironies
      and social concepts,

159
00:07:57,911 --> 00:08:00,779
      And I just found that
    really, really exciting.

160
00:08:00,781 --> 00:08:04,115
 -My mom died about 11 years ago
       of a heart attack,

161
00:08:04,117 --> 00:08:07,719
  And my husband is a huge fan
     of "calvin and hobbes,"

162
00:08:07,721 --> 00:08:09,120
         So he had a lot
  of the paperback collections

163
00:08:09,122 --> 00:08:10,889
    Laying around the house,

164
00:08:10,891 --> 00:08:13,992
  And I would just sit at night
     and look through those.

165
00:08:13,994 --> 00:08:16,962
  And that's how I came to know
       "calvin and hobbes"

166
00:08:16,964 --> 00:08:19,764
  Is through those first three
or four months after she passed.

167
00:08:19,766 --> 00:08:22,901
    It's just finding a place
         to laugh again.

168
00:08:22,903 --> 00:08:24,970
      -So I moved down here
    in this brand-new state,

169
00:08:24,972 --> 00:08:27,072
     This brand-new house,
     brand-new neighborhood,
     and I knew nobody.

170
00:08:27,074 --> 00:08:29,274
 So I was looking for something

171
00:08:29,276 --> 00:08:32,544
      To gravitate towards
       or associate with,

172
00:08:32,546 --> 00:08:35,881
 And "calvin and hobbes" became
   something I could bond with

173
00:08:35,883 --> 00:08:38,783
        On a daily basis
 when the newspaper would come.

174
00:08:38,785 --> 00:08:41,186
-I didn't understand, sometimes,

175
00:08:41,188 --> 00:08:44,189
        The significance
       of his statements,

176
00:08:44,191 --> 00:08:48,059
    But that really pushed me
          into research

177
00:08:48,061 --> 00:08:51,963
    And go to the dictionary
 or really looking for meaning.

178
00:08:51,965 --> 00:08:53,899
 -It's one of those things that,

179
00:08:53,901 --> 00:08:56,568
        When you find it,
      you want to share it.

180
00:08:56,570 --> 00:08:59,271
         And as soon as
     he could start reading,

181
00:08:59,273 --> 00:09:01,606
 I wanted to give him the books.

182
00:09:01,608 --> 00:09:03,808
     And just like I thought
           it would --

183
00:09:03,810 --> 00:09:05,243
    I mean, there's times now

184
00:09:05,245 --> 00:09:07,879
    Where he'll be reading it
         in his bedroom,

185
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:09,781
And I'll just hear him laughing.

186
00:09:09,783 --> 00:09:12,551
    And just that simple act
      of hearing him laugh

187
00:09:12,553 --> 00:09:15,754
  As I know what he's reading,
    it's like, "there you go.

188
00:09:15,756 --> 00:09:18,023
 That's what I was hoping for."

189
00:09:18,025 --> 00:09:21,059
    -I don't know if you know
  how israel was in 2002, 2001.

190
00:09:21,061 --> 00:09:22,260
      It was pretty crazy.

191
00:09:22,262 --> 00:09:23,762
    You opened the newspaper,

192
00:09:23,764 --> 00:09:25,864
   And you saw another bombing
           every day.

193
00:09:25,866 --> 00:09:27,198
     It was really intense.

194
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:29,868
       So I looked forward
       to the Sunday paper

195
00:09:29,870 --> 00:09:32,070
             Because
    they would run the strip,

196
00:09:32,072 --> 00:09:34,906
    And I'd cut them out and
 would hang them up on my wall.

197
00:09:34,908 --> 00:09:37,909
        Even if there was
something horrible in the paper,

198
00:09:37,911 --> 00:09:41,246
   I would still get my smile
and, you know, that good feeling

199
00:09:41,248 --> 00:09:44,115
     From just reading that.

200
00:09:44,117 --> 00:09:51,256
 It just relieves the stress of
 living in that kind of a world.

201
00:09:51,258 --> 00:09:54,125
     When we need something
         to smile about,

202
00:09:54,127 --> 00:09:57,095
        You just pull out
     one of the old comics,

203
00:09:57,097 --> 00:10:01,299
      And you just read it,
     and it brings you back.

204
00:10:01,301 --> 00:10:05,937
And that's the beauty of comics,
      especially "calvin."

205
00:10:05,939 --> 00:10:07,739
          [ chuckles ]

206
00:10:09,642 --> 00:10:12,611
        -For those of you
       who don't know him,

207
00:10:12,613 --> 00:10:14,212
     Calvin is a 6-year-old

208
00:10:14,214 --> 00:10:17,682
       Who some might call
    a bit of a troublemaker.

209
00:10:17,684 --> 00:10:20,352
          But he's also
     extremely intelligent,

210
00:10:20,354 --> 00:10:24,756
   With an endless imagination
and an incredible lust for life.

211
00:10:24,758 --> 00:10:27,926
     Hobbes is his ballast,
      his voice of reason,

212
00:10:27,928 --> 00:10:31,296
       His coconspirator,
      and loyal companion.

213
00:10:31,298 --> 00:10:36,067
  There's mom and dad, susie,
  rosalyn, moe, mrs. Wormwood,

214
00:10:36,069 --> 00:10:38,303
   And a few other characters.

215
00:10:38,305 --> 00:10:40,839
      But nobody else sees
      and understand hobbes

216
00:10:40,841 --> 00:10:42,273
      The way calvin does,

217
00:10:42,275 --> 00:10:47,012
    And it seems the reverse
   is probably true, as well.

218
00:10:47,014 --> 00:10:48,313
   -If I actually met someone

219
00:10:48,315 --> 00:10:49,948
       Who had never read
      "calvin and hobbes,"

220
00:10:49,950 --> 00:10:51,416
 Which does occasionally happen,

221
00:10:51,418 --> 00:10:54,152
  I would probably immediately
       just go to my desk,

222
00:10:54,154 --> 00:10:56,688
    Pull a book off, and say,
        "here, take this.

223
00:10:56,690 --> 00:10:58,990
          [ chuckling ]
  this will change your life."

224
00:10:58,992 --> 00:11:01,726
 It's so hard to just sum it up,

225
00:11:01,728 --> 00:11:05,764
       Other than to say,
   "this is every one of us."

226
00:11:05,766 --> 00:11:08,833
-Certainly, it's a family strip.
       It's a kids' strip.

227
00:11:08,835 --> 00:11:11,670
         In some senses,
 it's a gag-a-day kind of strip.

228
00:11:11,672 --> 00:11:13,271
            You know,
  there's always a punch line,

229
00:11:13,273 --> 00:11:15,173
  Some kind of gag at the end.

230
