00:22:20,640 --> 00:22:24,942
When the deer pop in with rifles

466
00:22:24,944 --> 00:22:30,815
     And shoot bill or phil
          or some guy.

467
00:22:32,017 --> 00:22:35,419
       His signature here

468
00:22:35,421 --> 00:22:38,356
Is a lot more like his signature
    with "calvin and hobbes."

469
00:22:38,358 --> 00:22:39,690
            -Mm-hmm.

470
00:22:42,928 --> 00:22:46,564
  -In the early '80s, watterson
  did have a few opportunities

471
00:22:46,566 --> 00:22:49,867
 To showcase his drawing skills
    for various publications

472
00:22:49,869 --> 00:22:53,404
    While he endured repeated
 rejection from the syndicates.

473
00:22:53,406 --> 00:22:56,807
But while he worked hard to make
    a living as a cartoonist,

474
00:22:56,809 --> 00:23:00,044
  His talents were often wasted
    on laying out advertising

475
00:23:00,046 --> 00:23:02,480
   In order to pay the bills.

476
00:23:02,482 --> 00:23:05,516
     Within months, however,
      of quitting that job,

477
00:23:05,518 --> 00:23:08,552
     Watterson was becoming
     one of the cartoonists

478
00:23:08,554 --> 00:23:10,955
     Who other professional
    and aspiring cartoonists

479
00:23:10,957 --> 00:23:13,824
       Were looking up to.

480
00:23:13,826 --> 00:23:16,594
       -It's probably hard
        to name an artist

481
00:23:16,596 --> 00:23:19,397
  Who came along in the 1990s,
            onward --

482
00:23:19,399 --> 00:23:21,766
     A comic-strip artist --

483
00:23:21,768 --> 00:23:24,769
      Who wasn't influenced
           in some way

484
00:23:24,771 --> 00:23:27,638
     By "calvin and hobbes."

485
00:23:27,640 --> 00:23:30,508
     -You can definitely see
   his impact in comics today,

486
00:23:30,510 --> 00:23:33,677
   And it's not that anyone is
 copying his comic specifically

487
00:23:33,679 --> 00:23:35,780
         Or trying to do
      exactly what he did.

488
00:23:35,782 --> 00:23:39,950
  But you can clearly see that
  the creators who are younger

489
00:23:39,952 --> 00:23:43,120
           And who are
  introducing new comic strips,

490
00:23:43,122 --> 00:23:45,956
    You can clearly see that
they've read "calvin and hobbes"

491
00:23:45,958 --> 00:23:48,459
   And are influenced by that.

492
00:23:48,461 --> 00:23:50,761
         -I can tell you
      when I saw calvin --

493
00:23:50,763 --> 00:23:53,697
    I saw the very first day
       in the <i>l.A. Times.</i>

494
00:23:53,699 --> 00:23:56,500
 I liked it, and you don't like
        strips very often

495
00:23:56,502 --> 00:23:58,068
 From the, you know, first day.

496
00:23:58,070 --> 00:24:00,838
  -I remember looking at comics
        in the newspaper

497
00:24:00,840 --> 00:24:02,606
    And thinking, "you know,

498
00:24:02,608 --> 00:24:05,142
 I could probably write and draw
     as well as these guys.

499
00:24:05,144 --> 00:24:07,912
   I should give a comic strip
            a shot."

500
00:24:07,914 --> 00:24:10,114
    After "calvin and hobbes"
            came out,

501
00:24:10,116 --> 00:24:11,749
    I sort of modified it to,

502
00:24:11,751 --> 00:24:13,451
     "well, I could probably
         write and draw

503
00:24:13,453 --> 00:24:15,085
 As well as most of these guys."

504
00:24:15,087 --> 00:24:17,755
   -I had sort of written off
 the comic strips at that point.

505
00:24:17,757 --> 00:24:20,090
  And when "calvin and hobbes"
    came fresh on the scene,

506
00:24:20,092 --> 00:24:23,694
        It was brand-new,
        and it was funny.

507
00:24:23,696 --> 00:24:25,062
        It captivated me
       right off the bat.

508
00:24:25,064 --> 00:24:26,497
  I knew that was a good strip.

509
00:24:26,499 --> 00:24:28,032
             I said
  I knew it was a funny strip.

510
00:24:28,034 --> 00:24:30,768
     I couldn't wait to read
  that strip every single day.

511
00:24:30,770 --> 00:24:35,706
-There was a unique perspective,
      a unique voice to it,

512
00:24:35,708 --> 00:24:40,644
         That it wasn't
   generic formula-gag stuff,

513
00:24:40,646 --> 00:24:43,781
         Which permeates
     most of the comic page.

514
00:24:43,783 --> 00:24:46,250
    -And in every way, shape,
    and form, on every level,

515
00:24:46,252 --> 00:24:48,652
           It was like
     comic-strip perfection.

516
00:24:48,654 --> 00:24:50,020
        And it still is.

517
00:24:50,022 --> 00:24:52,623
    -One of my favorite lines
    came from lynn johnston,

518
00:24:52,625 --> 00:24:54,658
          Who was doing
   "for better or for worse."

519
00:24:54,660 --> 00:24:56,260
          And she said,

520
00:24:56,262 --> 00:24:58,629
"you know, he inspires all of us
   to do a little bit better."

521
00:24:58,631 --> 00:25:02,233
        And I think that,
        on the one side,

522
00:25:02,235 --> 00:25:04,869
     Was a beneficial impact
          that he had,

523
00:25:04,871 --> 00:25:08,038
   Not only among the artists
  who were working at the time,

524
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:10,808
      But on younger people
    who were reading comics,

525
00:25:10,810 --> 00:25:13,277
 That there was this opportunity

526
00:25:13,279 --> 00:25:15,646
     To do different things
          with the art

527
00:25:15,648 --> 00:25:18,148
 And try to push the boundaries
          a little bit.

528
00:25:18,150 --> 00:25:20,684
     -My initial impression
       when I saw him was,

529
00:25:20,686 --> 00:25:23,287
  "the guy is making it harder
      for the rest of us,"

530
00:25:23,289 --> 00:25:24,722
      'cause he is setting

531
00:25:24,724 --> 00:25:26,891
    This ridiculous standard
          of excellence

532
00:25:26,893 --> 00:25:28,559
      That hadn't been seen
     since the "pogo" years,

533
00:25:28,561 --> 00:25:30,194
           In drawing.

534
00:25:30,196 --> 00:25:32,963
  -Most of the time, I was just
   trying to meet my deadline.

535
00:25:32,965 --> 00:25:35,599
   For bill, it wasn't enough
   to just meet the deadline.

536
00:25:35,601 --> 00:25:38,903
  You had to sort of, you know,
    move the bar a little bit

537
00:25:38,905 --> 00:25:40,871
Over what you'd done previously.

538
00:25:40,873 --> 00:25:43,207
             -It was
 a completely different approach

539
00:25:43,209 --> 00:25:45,609
       To the traditional
       four-panel strip.

540
00:25:45,611 --> 00:25:47,278
            There was
     just something about it

541
00:25:47,280 --> 00:25:49,246
          That was just
      very, very magical --

542
00:25:49,248 --> 00:25:51,315
     The way he drew trees,
     the way he drew water,

543
00:25:51,317 --> 00:25:53,017
    The way he drew movement.

544
00:25:53,019 --> 00:25:55,753
         -The brushwork
   just continues to amaze me,

545
00:25:55,755 --> 00:25:58,055
        And his writing,
       which is so concise

546
00:25:58,057 --> 00:26:00,257
         And yet so deep
       and philosophical.

547
00:26:00,259 --> 00:26:02,860
           -You know,
   his approach at philosophy

548
00:26:02,862 --> 00:26:05,796
    And sort of representing
       the human condition

549
00:26:05,798 --> 00:26:07,965
          Was something
     that was always bigger

550
00:26:07,967 --> 00:26:09,767
 Than just a little comic strip.

551
00:26:09,769 --> 00:26:13,904
        The conversations
 had so many layers of meaning.

552
00:26:13,906 --> 00:26:16,173
 And if I could even come close
            to that,

553
00:26:16,175 --> 00:26:17,975
 I would be absolutely thrilled.

554
00:26:17,977 --> 00:26:21,612
    -Bill watterson showed me

555
00:26:21,614 --> 00:26:24,148
   That a great, amazing comic

556
00:26:24,150 --> 00:26:27,318
        Is great writing
    that can stand on its own

557
00:26:27,320 --> 00:26:30,087
        And great drawing
   that can stand on its own.

558
00:26:30,089 --> 00:26:32,790
     You know, you take out
       either one of those

559
00:26:32,792 --> 00:26:34,892
              From
  a "calvin and hobbes" strip,

560
00:26:34,894 --> 00:26:37,194
      And it's still great
           to look at.

561
00:26:37,196 --> 00:26:38,996
    It's still funny to read.

562
00:26:38,998 --> 00:26:40,698
       Put them together,

563
00:26:40,700 --> 00:26:43,968
And you have one of the greatest
    comic strips of all time.

564
00:26:43,970 --> 00:26:46,770
      -"calvin and hobbes,"
  as far as a comic strip goes,

565
00:26:46,772 --> 00:26:50,007
 Was such a huge influence on me
 wanting to become a cartoonist.

566
00:26:50,009 --> 00:26:52,309
        It was everything
    a comic strip should be.

567
00:26:52,311 --> 00:26:55,079
 It's very dynamic. It's funny.
    It's got a strong voice.

568
00:26:55,081 --> 00:26:56,914
            You know,
    the artwork is fabulous.

569
00:26:56,916 --> 00:26:59,183
      There wasn't anything
      not to like about it.

570
00:26:59,185 --> 00:27:02,019
          -If he's not
    the most cited influence,

571
00:27:02,021 --> 00:27:05,089
     He's certainly second,
  behind schulz and "peanuts."

572
00:27:05,091 --> 00:27:06,924
       But he's up there.

573
00:27:06,926 --> 00:27:09,326
   And I think we get so many
 submissions that say, you know,

574
00:27:09,328 --> 00:27:11,261
   "I've always been a big fan
     of 'calvin and hobbes,'

575
00:27:11,263 --> 00:27:13,030
So I wanted to try and do this."

576
00:27:13,032 --> 00:27:14,398
      -I think you can see

577
00:27:14,400 --> 00:27:17,067
          An influence
     of "calvin and hobbes,"

578
00:27:17,069 --> 00:27:21,071
     To a degree, in "zits,"
    a strip I like very much.

579
00:27:21,073 --> 00:27:24,008
       There is a kind of
       calvin-esque feel

580
00:27:24,010 --> 00:27:27,311
   To the way that jim borgman
         and jerry scott

581
00:27:27,313 --> 00:27:32,816
    Will play jeremy duncan's
 fantasies against the reality.

582
00:27:32,818 --> 00:27:35,152
 -As a professional cartoonist,
         I read it now,

583
00:27:35,154 --> 00:27:37,354
        And you just see
     a master at his craft,

584
00:27:37,356 --> 00:27:40,658
     You know, someone that
  [chuckles] puts you to shame

585
00:27:40,660 --> 00:27:43,394
As far as what you're able to do
         in comparison.

586
00:27:43,396 --> 00:27:47,297
-I actually have a comic that I
had to do for a class in college

587
00:27:47,299 --> 00:27:49,133
  At the school of visual arts.

588
00:27:49,135 --> 00:27:52,403
     So we had to do a comic
  about our biggest influence.

589
00:27:52,405 --> 00:27:55,172
  Of course, what else would I
  pick but "calvin and hobbes"?

590
00:27:55,174 --> 00:27:58,008
  One of the things that I feel
     that I gained the most,

591
00:27:58,010 --> 00:28:00,210
        As a cartoonist,
    from reading this strip,

592
00:28:00,212 --> 00:28:04,114
      Is learning how to do
such wild and crazy expressions.

593
00:28:04,116 --> 00:28:06,450
          And sometimes
   it's not just the writing.

594
00:28:06,452 --> 00:28:08,852
            It's just
   the simplest, crazy drawing

595
00:28:08,854 --> 00:28:12,156
   That will make you laugh or
 smile and really influence you.

596
00:28:12,158 --> 00:28:15,426
       So I was very happy
    to get my inner calvin on

597
00:28:15,428 --> 00:28:18,429
           [chuckles]
   while working on the strip.

598
00:28:20,899 --> 00:28:22,966
    -I got a lot of attention

599
00:28:22,968 --> 00:28:26,370
        For a resemblance
     to "calvin and hobbes."

600
00:28:26,372 --> 00:28:29,139
         And some of it
   was very, very flattering,

601
00:28:29,141 --> 00:28:31,442
         And some of it
      was less flattering,

602
00:28:31,444 --> 00:28:33,977
 And some it was flat-out mean.

603
00:28:33,979 --> 00:28:36,213
             I tried
   not to take it personally.

604
00:28:36,215 --> 00:28:38,382
             I mean,
  the people who were outraged

605
00:28:38,384 --> 00:28:40,751
    That my strip might bear
         any resemblance

606
00:28:40,753 --> 00:28:42,219
     To "calvin and hobbes,"

607
00:28:42,221 --> 00:28:44,788
  I think that was done mostly
    out of a passionate love

608
00:28:44,790 --> 00:28:46,390
    For "calvin and hobbes."

609
00:28:46,392 --> 00:28:48,992
  And anything that you write
  is gonna be autobiographical

610
00:28:48,994 --> 00:28:50,427
          At its heart.

611
00:28:50,429 --> 00:28:52,129
       Same with "frazz."
     you know, frazz is me.

612
00:28:52,131 --> 00:28:55,099
     He's cooler than I am,
because I can make him that way,

613
00:28:55,101 --> 00:28:56,433
          But he's me.

614
00:28:56,435 --> 00:28:59,436
         And, likewise,
   if I learned a whole bunch

615
00:28:59,438 --> 00:29:02,873
    From "calvin and hobbes,"
      from bill watterson,

616
00:29:02,875 --> 00:29:04,274
  I'm not gonna cover that up.

617
00:29:04,276 --> 00:29:06,910
            Honestly,
    I think it would be rude

618
00:29:06,912 --> 00:29:09,246
    To try and say, "oh, no,
    I did this all on my own.

619
00:29:09,248 --> 00:29:12,015
    This is all me. I didn't
    learn this from anybody."

620
00:29:12,017 --> 00:29:16,253
    No. We're all standing on
    the shoulders of giants.

621
00:29:16,255 --> 00:29:21,859
  -Watterson certainly left us
    a legacy of great ideas,

622
00:29:21,861 --> 00:29:25,763
         Great drawing,
      great, great comics,

623
00:29:25,765 --> 00:29:27,831
 But he was last in a long line

624
00:29:27,833 --> 00:29:31,301
  Of really amazing cartoonists
     from the 20th century,

625
00:29:31,303 --> 00:29:35,973
     Since the real blooming
  of the comic-strip art form.

626
00:29:35,975 --> 00:29:39,443
And he very much valued the work
         of walt kelly,

627
00:29:39,445 --> 00:29:44,014
  One of the cartoonists that I
 loved to read when I was a kid.

628
00:29:44,016 --> 00:29:45,349
     If you look at "pogo,"

629
00:29:45,351 --> 00:29:47,785
        You can see that
   he very strongly influenced

630
00:29:47,787 --> 00:29:49,052
     Not only bill watterson

631
00:29:49,054 --> 00:29:51,155
      But also jeff smith,
        who does "bone."

632
00:29:51,157 --> 00:29:55,092
  "pogo" was this world similar
   to what watterson created,

633
00:29:55,094 --> 00:29:58,862
 Where there were these animals
      and these characters,

634
00:29:58,864 --> 00:30:00,297
   And they spoke about things

635
00:30:00,299 --> 00:30:02,199
   Much bigger than the swamp
       that they lived in.

636
00:30:02,201 --> 00:30:07,471
They were possums and alligators
and chicks and all these things,

637
00:30:07,473 --> 00:30:10,507
    But they were politicians
        and philosophers,

638
00:30:10,509 --> 00:30:13,811
   And they commented heavily
           on society.

639
00:30:13,813 --> 00:30:15,312
        So I can imagine

640
00:30:15,314 --> 00:30:18,048
   Why watterson found "pogo"
     fascinating to look at,

641
00:30:18,050 --> 00:30:20,450
   And it's beautifully drawn,
        and walt kelly --

642
00:30:20,452 --> 00:30:24,888
 You know, just no end of genius
    in how he created "pogo."

643
00:30:24,890 --> 00:30:26,356
     -Schulz is, of course,

644
00:30:26,358 --> 00:30:29,526
  Such an important cartoonist
      and such a great one

645
00:30:29,528 --> 00:30:32,129
         That, I think,
   pretty much any comic strip

646
00:30:32,131 --> 00:30:36,200
 That began after the early '50s
      was influenced by it.

647
00:30:36,202 --> 00:30:39,436
    The scale of the stories
         he would tell,

648
00:30:39,438 --> 00:30:43,240
    The intimacy of the strip
      and of the settings,

649
00:30:43,242 --> 00:30:46,543
        The observations
      of children's lives,

650
00:30:46,545 --> 00:30:48,345
       All I think, again,

651
00:30:48,347 --> 00:30:52,316
    Can be seen as influences
     on "calvin and hobbes."

652
00:30:52,318 --> 00:30:57,187
  Just the notion of the world
  from a child's point of view

653
00:30:57,189 --> 00:30:59,890
 Was something that schulz took,

654
00:30:59,892 --> 00:31:03,393
     And while other artists
 had done things with it before,

655
00:31:03,395 --> 00:31:07,564
  Schulz did it so much better
    and had so much influence

656
00:31:07,566 --> 00:31:10,167
That, once again, you can see it

657
00:31:10,169 --> 00:31:13,003
          Flowing into
      "calvin and hobbes."

658
00:31:13,005 --> 00:31:15,005
             -Well,
  I don't know bill watterson,

659
00:31:15,007 --> 00:31:17,207
       So I don't want to
      speak to his motives,

660
00:31:17,209 --> 00:31:19,509
      But it appears to me,
      in reading his essays

661
00:31:19,511 --> 00:31:22,079
     And seeing some of his
  interviews about "krazy kat,"

662
00:31:22,081 --> 00:31:25,883
   That "krazy kat" set a bar
 that he judged his own work by

663
00:31:25,885 --> 00:31:28,952
   And would not be satisfied
        with his own work

664
00:31:28,954 --> 00:31:32,556
 If it wasn't as idiosyncratic,
         as imaginative,

665
00:31:32,558 --> 00:31:36,226
 As personal as "krazy kat" was.

666
00:31:36,228 --> 00:31:38,328
         Watterson said,
      in his first hiatus,

667
00:31:38,330 --> 00:31:40,130
He started paying more attention

668
00:31:40,132 --> 00:31:42,633
   To what herriman was doing
      on those full pages,

669
00:31:42,635 --> 00:31:45,202
     When the newspaper page
       was a blank canvas

670
00:31:45,204 --> 00:31:48,071
     And he could have form
     be dictated by content

671
00:31:48,073 --> 00:31:49,640
Instead of the other way around,

672
00:31:49,642 --> 00:31:52,075
       Instead of saying,
 "you've got eight panels here.

673
00:31:52,077 --> 00:31:54,311
            You know,
that's gonna be your narrative."

674
00:31:54,313 --> 00:31:57,247
            Instead,
   he could blow it wide-open,

675
00:31:57,249 --> 00:31:59,182
 Have the panels not be panels,

676
00:31:59,184 --> 00:32:02,219
  You know, have the adventure,
       the narrative flow

677
00:32:02,221 --> 00:32:04,388
     Follow whatever course,
          artistically,

678
00:32:04,390 --> 00:32:06,456
     That he wanted to take.

679
00:32:06,458 --> 00:32:09,927
  All that stuff that herriman
   gave himself license to do

680
00:32:09,929 --> 00:32:11,495
   Is right there on the page.

681
00:32:11,497 --> 00:32:14,665
  So I think, for a cartoonist,
     it represented freedom.

682
00:32:14,667 --> 00:32:18,035
    It represented personal,
  artistic, visionary freedom.

683
00:32:18,037 --> 00:32:23,040
   I think he saw that and saw
 this was what he could do, too.

684
00:32:36,554 --> 00:32:40,157
 -There is something else deep
 in the basement of the library

685
00:32:40,159 --> 00:32:42,192
        In chagrin falls.

686
00:32:42,194 --> 00:32:44,494
            Watterson
   lent his photography skills

687
00:32:44,496 --> 00:32:46,263
  To his high-school yearbook,

688
00:32:46,265 --> 00:32:50,300
        And his cartoons
    are scattered throughout.

689
00:32:50,302 --> 00:32:51,668
       One of his drawings

690
00:32:51,670 --> 00:32:54,504
        Is a depiction of
the four photographers on staff,

691
00:32:54,506 --> 00:32:56,206
      As the caption reads,

692
00:32:56,208 --> 00:33:00,477
      "watterson is the one
  on the far right, blinking."

693
00:33:00,479 --> 00:33:04,648
Perhaps this drawing foreshadows
  watterson's future reputation

694
00:33:04,650 --> 00:33:08,018
 For being a man who shied away
       from the spotlight

695
00:33:08,020 --> 00:33:12,089
      And very much desired
          his privacy.

696
00:33:12,091 --> 00:33:13,991
      -I think, initially,
         he was pleased

697
00:33:13,993 --> 00:33:15,759
       That so many papers
        were signing on.

698
00:33:15,761 --> 00:33:18,662
       He started getting
       a lot of fan mail.

699
00:33:18,664 --> 00:33:21,131
He got a lot of press attention,

700
00:33:21,133 --> 00:33:23,500
    And he realized, I think,
        pretty quickly on

701
00:33:23,502 --> 00:33:25,569
   That he had done something
            special.

702
00:33:25,571 --> 00:33:28,271
           And I think
     it didn't take him long

703
00:33:28,273 --> 00:33:31,708
   To become a little unnerved
     and taken aback by it.

704
00:33:31,710 --> 00:33:35,312
           -Even with
    a tiny amount of success,

705
00:33:35,314 --> 00:33:40,450
It's a little daunting how much
feedback and comment and request

706
00:33:40,452 --> 00:33:43,153
You get from the general public.

707
00:33:43,155 --> 00:33:46,023
      So I can only imagine
      if I'm bill watterson

708
00:33:46,025 --> 00:33:51,028
And I have millions and millions
  and millions of adoring fans.

709
00:33:51,030 --> 00:33:53,096
  -Nobody knows bill watterson.

710
00:33:53,098 --> 00:33:54,631
     There's like three
     people on the planet
     who have ever seen him.

711
00:33:54,633 --> 00:33:56,333
    He won't talk to anybody.

712
00:33:56,335 --> 00:33:58,635
       He's the sasquatch
         of cartoonists.

713
00:33:58,637 --> 00:34:00,670
            You know,
 people have seen his footprint,

714
00:34:00,672 --> 00:34:02,806
       But nobody has ever
    gotten a picture of him.

715
00:34:02,808 --> 00:34:05,175
         -He just wanted
    to draw his comic strip.

716
00:34:05,177 --> 00:34:07,344
        He didn't really
       want to be famous.

717
00:34:07,346 --> 00:34:09,746
He didn't want all the trappings
       that went with it.

718
00:34:09,748 --> 00:34:13,250
 He just wanted to do a good job
     drawing a comic strip.

719
00:34:13,252 --> 00:34:17,754
      -Cartooning attracts
        solitary people,

720
00:34:17,756 --> 00:34:20,657
  Quiet people, insular people.

721
00:34:20,659 --> 00:34:23,393
   Because, if you were gonna
spend time at your drawing desk,

722
00:34:23,395 --> 00:34:25,796
 You weren't the kind of person
 that dated well in high school.

723
00:34:25,798 --> 00:34:27,197
      You know what I mean?

724
00:34:27,199 --> 00:34:28,565
 You weren't the kind of person

725
00:34:28,567 --> 00:34:30,233
      That was the captain
      of the football team.

726
00:34:30,235 --> 00:34:32,803
       For the most part,
 it's people that use their art

727
00:34:32,805 --> 00:34:35,372
       To make their voice
     to the world, you know?

728
00:34:35,374 --> 00:34:41,478
    So it doesn't surprise me
 that he errs on the shier side,

729
00:34:41,480 --> 00:34:44,781
      The introverted side,
       the reclusive side.

730
00:34:44,783 --> 00:34:48,351
Because that's probably what his
  life framed him as, you know?

731
00:34:48,353 --> 00:34:51,555
   He was probably always shy
 and introverted and reclusive,

732
00:34:51,557 --> 00:34:53,757
    Or else he wouldn't have
        spent the decades

733
00:34:53,759 --> 00:34:56,293
     Crafting his abilities
     as an artist, you know?

734
00:34:56,295 --> 00:34:58,195
          He would have
      been out socializing

735
00:34:58,197 --> 00:34:59,830
           And become
    a regional sales manager

736
00:34:59,832 --> 00:35:01,565
 For midas car parts, you know?

737
00:35:01,567 --> 00:35:05,402
   I mean, it would have been
   a different path in life.

738
00:35:05,404 --> 00:35:09,239
   -Luckily, watterson didn't
    end up selling car parts

739
00:35:09,241 --> 00:35:12,242
        And he did create
      "calvin and hobbes."

740
00:35:12,244 --> 00:35:15,212
           By the end
 of its decade-long syndication,

741
00:35:15,214 --> 00:35:18,181
 It was in over 2,400 newspapers
           worldwide,

742
00:35:18,183 --> 00:35:20,617
     With a daily readership
          of millions.

743
00:35:20,619 --> 00:35:23,487
 Watterson won the reuben award
   for cartoonist of the year

744
00:35:23,489 --> 00:35:25,889
        In 1986 and 1988,

745
00:35:25,891 --> 00:35:28,792
        The harvey award
 for best syndicated comic strip

746
00:35:28,794 --> 00:35:30,227
      Seven years in a row,

747
00:35:30,229 --> 00:35:31,495
     And "calvin and hobbes"

748
00:35:31,497 --> 00:35:33,763
Was loved by readers and critics
             alike.

749
00:35:33,765 --> 00:35:36,299
     18 "calvin and hobbes"
        book collections

750
00:35:36,301 --> 00:35:38,201
Have been published in the u.S.,

751
00:35:38,203 --> 00:35:40,604
   Selling 45 million copies,

752
00:35:40,606 --> 00:35:43,540
    And dozens more have been
    published internationally

753
00:35:43,542 --> 00:35:46,209
In at least two dozen languages.

754
00:35:46,211 --> 00:35:49,312
   There are frequent homages
 and spoofs on the comics pages,

755
00:35:49,314 --> 00:35:51,281
          And the strip
       has been referenced

756
00:35:51,283 --> 00:35:52,782
 In numerous american tv shows,

757
00:35:52,784 --> 00:35:56,186
     Including "family guy,"
     "the big bang theory,"

758
00:35:56,188 --> 00:35:59,156
      "parks and reaction,"
          "portlandia,"

759
00:35:59,158 --> 00:36:00,891
      And "robot chicken."

760
00:36:00,893 --> 00:36:03,760
       But bill watterson
  doesn't seem to care too much

761
00:36:03,762 --> 00:36:06,696
 About the numbers or the awards
        or the accolades.

762
00:36:06,698 --> 00:36:09,499
            His focus
 was on the comic strip itself,

763
00:36:09,501 --> 00:36:11,434
 Which, despite being something

764
00:36:11,436 --> 00:36:13,837
     That watterson has said
       he did for himself,

765
00:36:13,839 --> 00:36:17,474
    Had become very important
      to readers worldwide.

766
00:36:17,476 --> 00:36:20,710
      -Bill watterson saved
 almost all of the original art

767
00:36:20,712 --> 00:36:22,379
    From "calvin and hobbes,"

768
00:36:22,381 --> 00:36:24,381
Both the dailies and the sundays

769
00:36:24,383 --> 00:36:26,716
     And all of the book art
          that he did,

770
00:36:26,718 --> 00:36:29,452
  And he put it on deposit here

771
00:36:29,454 --> 00:36:31,888
      At the billy ireland
    cartoon library & museum.

772
00:36:31,890 --> 00:36:33,590
   So were are the caretakers,

773
00:36:33,592 --> 00:36:36,293
      And we make sure that
  it's preserved and kept safe

774
00:36:36,295 --> 00:36:40,230
 And, also, that it's accessible
  to researchers and scholars.

775
00:36:40,232 --> 00:36:42,899
So if somebody wants to come and
 actually see the original art,

776
00:36:42,901 --> 00:36:45,335
      They can come to our
  reading room and request it,

777
00:36:45,337 --> 00:36:47,537
    And we'll bring it out,
    and they can look at it.

778
00:36:47,539 --> 00:36:50,240
           So this is
    what we call the stacks,

779
00:36:50,242 --> 00:36:53,210
   And this is obviously where
 we keep all of our collection.

780
00:36:53,212 --> 00:36:55,345
           We operate
     like a rare-books room,

781
00:36:55,347 --> 00:36:56,746
     So nothing circulates,

782
00:36:56,748 --> 00:36:58,448
     Nothing actually leaves
      the cartoon library.

783
00:36:58,450 --> 00:37:00,217
           If anybody
     wants to use something,

784
00:37:00,219 --> 00:37:02,352
 They have to actually come here
         and request it,

785
00:37:02,354 --> 00:37:04,588
    And then we bring it out,
     and you can look at it.

786
00:37:04,590 --> 00:37:08,792
           So we have
 over 400,000 original cartoons,

787
00:37:08,794 --> 00:37:11,528
 Including, of course, the bill
 watterson deposit collection.

788
00:37:11,530 --> 00:37:13,997
    We have many, many books
  about cartoons, periodicals.

789
00:37:13,999 --> 00:37:15,765
      We have comic books.

790
00:37:15,767 --> 00:37:17,767
 We also have archival material,

791
00:37:17,769 --> 00:37:21,238
    So we collect the papers
   and letters of cartoonists

792
00:37:21,240 --> 00:37:22,906
        And other people
    related to the business.

793
00:37:22,908 --> 00:37:26,576
     This is gonna be all of
   your books about cartoons,

794
00:37:26,578 --> 00:37:29,646
   Anthologies, reprint books,
          how-to books,

795
00:37:29,648 --> 00:37:34,251
Journals like <i>pokk</i> or <i>judge</i> that
have a lot of cartoons in them.

796
00:37:34,253 --> 00:37:37,587
      And then, over here,
     we have our flat files,

797
00:37:37,589 --> 00:37:40,457
            Which is
    all of the original art.

798
00:37:40,459 --> 00:37:42,859
           So, this is
   one of my favorite drawers.

799
00:37:42,861 --> 00:37:46,463
    This is our "little nemo"
        by winsor mccay.

800
00:37:46,465 --> 00:37:49,366
          And these are
  just absolutely spectacular.

801
00:37:49,368 --> 00:37:50,867
        -That is massive.

802
00:37:50,869 --> 00:37:52,636
              -Yes.

803
00:37:52,638 --> 00:37:55,505
 Of course, the newspaper pages
     were bigger themselves,

804
00:37:55,507 --> 00:37:57,407
          At the time,

805
00:37:57,409 --> 00:37:59,442
 But it would have been smaller
 than he did it as the original.

806
00:37:59,444 --> 00:38:01,945
   "little nemo," of course,
   is a wonderful comic strip

807
00:38:01,947 --> 00:38:04,481
       About a little boy
 who goes to sleep every night,

808
00:38:04,483 --> 00:38:06,583
   And he goes to slumberland

809
00:38:06,585 --> 00:38:08,585
             And has
  all these amazing adventures.

810
00:38:08,587 --> 00:38:11,688
        And then, always
 on the last panel, he wakes up

811
00:38:11,690 --> 00:38:14,024
     And is back in his bed
    and is back into reality,

812
00:38:14,026 --> 00:38:16,826
   And so you can see how this
    influenced bill watterson

813
00:38:16,828 --> 00:38:18,395
    With "calvin and hobbes."

814
00:38:18,397 --> 00:38:20,530
    There are a lot of strips
       that are like that,

815
00:38:20,532 --> 00:38:21,931
          Where he's in
    kind of a fantasy world,

816
00:38:21,933 --> 00:38:23,566
  And then, in the last panel,
           he wakes up

817
00:38:23,568 --> 00:38:27,003
    Or comes back to reality.

818
00:38:33,844 --> 00:38:36,780
     -If you had the chance
       to view a selection

819
00:38:36,782 --> 00:38:39,082
     Of "calvin and hobbes"
           originals,

820
00:38:39,084 --> 00:38:41,318
       How would you pick
      which strips to see?

821
00:38:42,820 --> 00:38:46,389
Would you pick specific examples
         of panel layout

822
00:38:46,391 --> 00:38:49,526
    Or use of black-and-white
       or line techniques?

823
00:38:49,528 --> 00:38:52,962
   Maybe a daily and a Sunday
         from each year?

824
00:38:52,964 --> 00:38:57,067
Or would you just narrow it down
   to your absolute favorites?

825
00:38:59,337 --> 00:39:01,805
            No matter
    what you finally decide,

826
00:39:01,807 --> 00:39:05,575
Once you put on the white gloves
  and sit down with the strips,

827
00:39:05,577 --> 00:39:07,977
      I don't really think
        you can go wrong.

828
00:39:09,413 --> 00:39:12,382
         It's admittedly
      a strange experience.

829
00:39:12,384 --> 00:39:15,118
         You can examine
      each line and letter

830
00:39:15,120 --> 00:39:17,387
   And mistake and alteration.

831
00:39:17,389 --> 00:39:19,522
           And you can
      compare the originals

832
00:39:19,524 --> 00:39:22,025
    To the printed newspaper
        or book version.

833
00:39:22,027 --> 00:39:24,994
      The dailies look much
      as you might expect,

834
00:39:24,996 --> 00:39:27,897
      But the Sunday strips
       are another story.

835
00:39:27,899 --> 00:39:32,135
   You can explore watterson's
      lush watercolor art,

836
00:39:32,137 --> 00:39:35,939
    But the Sunday originals
      are black-and-white.

837
00:39:35,941 --> 00:39:39,776
   They're incredible to see,
   despite the missing color.

838
00:39:39,778 --> 00:39:41,644
       But the experience
         got me thinking

839
00:39:41,646 --> 00:39:43,446
          About the art
       of the comic strip.

840
00:39:43,448 --> 00:39:46,483
             Comics
  are a bit of a unique medium

841
00:39:46,485 --> 00:39:49,652
   In that it can be difficult
            to define

842
00:39:49,654 --> 00:39:53,623
  Exactly what the final piece
       of art actually is.

843
00:39:53,625 --> 00:39:56,159
      Watterson's originals
       are probably worth

844
00:39:56,161 --> 00:39:58,728
  Tens of thousands of dollars
             apiece.

845
00:39:58,730 --> 00:40:00,430
       But it isn't until

846
00:40:00,432 --> 00:40:03,099
  The Sunday strips are printed
    in the paper or in books

847
00:40:03,101 --> 00:40:05,902
  That they reach their final,
         intended state.

848
00:40:05,904 --> 00:40:10,073
 If you think for just a moment
 about how prevalent comics are

849
00:40:10,075 --> 00:40:13,977
 And how many millions of prints
       of each daily strip

850
00:40:13,979 --> 00:40:16,780
         Are distributed
       across the planet,

851
00:40:16,782 --> 00:40:18,848
 It might be easy to understand

852
00:40:18,850 --> 00:40:22,452
    How comics might be often
     categorized as low art,

853
00:40:22,454 --> 00:40:25,955
      But it's hard to deny
       their high impact.

854
00:40:30,795 --> 00:40:35,198
  -I think he very quickly grew
              from,

855
00:40:35,200 --> 00:40:39,135
 "let me get a package together
 that a syndicate will pick up,"

856
00:40:39,137 --> 00:40:42,872
   To, "gosh, I got picked up,
  and I'm gonna be syndicated,"

857
00:40:42,874 --> 00:40:45,508
To, "now I have this opportunity

858
00:40:45,510 --> 00:40:49,679
    To kind of explore these
  different artistic options."

859
00:40:49,681 --> 00:40:52,482
But I think he quickly picked up
        the opportunities

860
00:40:52,484 --> 00:40:54,484
     With color on sundays,

861
00:40:54,486 --> 00:40:56,986
           The ability
   to push out the boundaries

862
00:40:56,988 --> 00:40:59,756
     On that piece of canvas
         on the sundays.

863
00:40:59,758 --> 00:41:01,224
   And, also, on the dailies,

864
00:41:01,226 --> 00:41:04,093
   He tried so many different
      things in the dailies

865
00:41:04,095 --> 00:41:07,897
  As just from the perspective
          of an artist.

866
00:41:07,899 --> 00:41:11,167
   -Cartoon art and comic art
  is something that, you know,

867
00:41:11,169 --> 00:41:15,004
 Was originally seen as kind of
     trashy, populist stuff,

868
00:41:15,006 --> 00:41:17,507
      Almost very childish.

869
00:41:17,509 --> 00:41:19,809
            And then,
   as the years have gone on,

870
00:41:19,811 --> 00:41:22,712
  You know, people have started
     to see the worth in it.

871
00:41:22,714 --> 00:41:27,217
 And that's because comic strips
 have tackled heavier subjects.

872
00:41:27,219 --> 00:41:31,654
The artwork has been elevated to
a massive degree in some cases.

873
00:41:31,656 --> 00:41:34,557
     -I don't understand the
  distinction that people make.

874
00:41:34,559 --> 00:41:36,192
    So you can have fine art.

875
00:41:36,194 --> 00:41:38,928
   You can have these amazing
 images that people acknowledge,

876
00:41:38,930 --> 00:41:41,731
            You know,
    can speak about any topic

877
00:41:41,733 --> 00:41:43,967
      And say great things

878
00:41:43,969 --> 00:41:48,771
           And reflect
what the artist is trying to do.

879
00:41:48,773 --> 00:41:51,040
     You can have literature
      that does that, too.

880
00:41:51,042 --> 00:41:52,942
   You can have a great novel
       that people respect

881
00:41:52,944 --> 00:41:54,644
      And they understand.

882
00:41:54,646 --> 00:41:57,714
  But, somehow, if you combine
    the words and the images,

883
00:41:57,716 --> 00:42:01,017
  All of a sudden, all you get
     is something for kids.

884
00:42:01,019 --> 00:42:02,685
        And why is that?

885
00:42:02,687 --> 00:42:05,088
       If you read through
   all of "calvin and hobbes,"

886
00:42:05,090 --> 00:42:08,558
 You'll see that he really has
 very interesting things to say

887
00:42:08,560 --> 00:42:11,828
 About society, about humanity,

888
00:42:11,830 --> 00:42:14,697
      About relationships,
        about the world.

889
00:42:14,699 --> 00:42:17,800
  And there's no reason why he
 can't do that in a comic strip.

890
00:42:17,802 --> 00:42:20,570
 That's a perfectly valid form.

891
00:42:20,572 --> 00:42:22,305
        And I'm thrilled
    that he chose that form,

892
00:42:22,307 --> 00:42:24,807
  Because I think he could have
     done probably anything.

893
00:42:24,809 --> 00:42:26,276
       He could have been
       just a fine artist.

894
00:42:26,278 --> 00:42:27,877
  He could have written books.

895
00:42:27,879 --> 00:42:30,179
 But he actually chose to do it
        as a comic strip,

896
00:42:30,181 --> 00:42:32,081
     And I'm grateful to him
            for that,

897
00:42:32,083 --> 00:42:33,650
   Because he did it so well,

898
00:42:33,652 --> 00:42:38,688
          And he showed
  how it could really be done.

899
00:42:38,690 --> 00:42:41,157
    My favorite strip, which
 probably doesn't surprise you,

900
00:42:41,159 --> 00:42:43,826
     Is the one where calvin
 and hobbes are looking at art,

901
00:42:43,828 --> 00:42:46,296
    And they're talking about
        comics versus art

902
00:42:46,298 --> 00:42:49,098
 And how you can have high art,
        like a painting,

903
00:42:49,100 --> 00:42:52,101
   And then you have low art,
   which is the comic strip,

904
00:42:52,103 --> 00:42:54,604
       And it's commercial
       and it's hack work.

905
00:42:54,606 --> 00:42:57,941
    And then he kind of shows
       how absurd that is

906
00:42:57,943 --> 00:43:01,711
     By saying, "a painting
    of a comic strip panel --

907
00:43:01,713 --> 00:43:03,947
  That's sophisticated irony,
  philosophically challenging.

908
00:43:03,949 --> 00:43:05,582
        That's high art."

909
00:43:05,584 --> 00:43:07,183
    And so then hobbes says,

910
00:43:07,185 --> 00:43:10,019
"well, suppose I draw a cartoon
of a painting of a comic strip."

911
00:43:10,021 --> 00:43:12,255
  And, you know, at that point,
        it's just absurd,

912
00:43:12,257 --> 00:43:14,657
        But calvin says,
     "no, that's sophomoric.

913
00:43:14,659 --> 00:43:16,993
  It's intellectually sterile.
         It's low art."

914
00:43:16,995 --> 00:43:19,762
     So he's commenting here
    exactly on this debate --

915
00:43:19,764 --> 00:43:22,065
   You know, what's high art?
         What's low art?

916
00:43:22,067 --> 00:43:25,301
   And why, just because it's
   printed in a newspaper
   and it's a comic strip,

917
00:43:25,303 --> 00:43:27,337
  Is it automatically low art?

918
00:43:27,339 --> 00:43:30,340
   I don't think anybody would
   look at "calvin and hobbes"

919
00:43:30,342 --> 00:43:33,209
    And say that it's not art
    or say that it's low art.

920
00:43:33,211 --> 00:43:35,144
      But that seems to be
          a distinction

921
00:43:35,146 --> 00:43:37,313
      That comic-strip art
      has been stuck with.

922
00:43:37,315 --> 00:43:40,016
  -Comics are self-expression.

923
00:43:40,018 --> 00:43:42,185
     Self-expression is art.

924
00:43:42,187 --> 00:43:45,288
        I don't give a...

925
00:43:45,290 --> 00:43:49,025
    About what an art critic
        might say art is

926
00:43:49,027 --> 00:43:55,098
         Because I know
  that I'm creating something.

927
00:43:55,100 --> 00:44:00,036
          Art is about
 creating something -- the end.

928
00:44:00,038 --> 00:44:02,405
        -If you actually
   still have a subscription,

929
00:44:02,407 --> 00:44:05,008
     You can probably tell
     newspapers are hurting

930
00:44:05,010 --> 00:44:07,844
     Simply by stepping out
   on your porch to get yours.

931
00:44:07,846 --> 00:44:10,079
    Nearly 100% of the time,

932
00:44:10,081 --> 00:44:12,348
     It isn't the front page
         that greets me

933
00:44:12,350 --> 00:44:16,119
       But a full-page ad
for a sports-equipment retailer.

934
00:44:16,121 --> 00:44:19,355
Then, the state of the perceived
  value of the comics is clear

935
00:44:19,357 --> 00:44:21,824
      When you try to find
      the comics section.

936
00:44:21,826 --> 00:44:23,860
     When I was growing up,

937
00:44:23,862 --> 00:44:26,329
 Depending on how your paperboy
    put together your paper,

938
00:44:26,331 --> 00:44:30,166
    The Sunday comics section
    was often the front page
    of the Sunday newspaper

939
00:44:30,168 --> 00:44:32,201
  When it arrived at your door.

940
00:44:32,203 --> 00:44:34,337
 It was the first thing you saw.

941
00:44:34,339 --> 00:44:38,841
Now it takes me a couple minutes
       just to locate it.

942
00:44:38,843 --> 00:44:41,144
         In looking back
 at comics sections of the past

943
00:44:41,146 --> 00:44:42,845
         In comparison,

944
00:44:42,847 --> 00:44:46,015
    It's clear just how much
  the comics are being trimmed.

945
00:44:46,017 --> 00:44:48,785
  A typical "calvin and hobbes"
         from the 1990s

946
00:44:48,787 --> 00:44:51,721
        Wouldn't even fit
    in todays Sunday funnies.

947
00:44:51,723 --> 00:44:53,890
            Watterson
   had more space on the page

948
00:44:53,892 --> 00:44:56,159
       Than "stone soup,"
       "in the bleachers,"

949
00:44:56,161 --> 00:45:01,130
"candorville," "frazz," and half
   of "non sequitur" combined.

950
00:45:01,132 --> 00:45:03,766
 -The comics page was shrinking
          in the 1980s.

951
00:45:03,768 --> 00:45:06,235
     It was getting smaller
    and smaller and smaller,

952
00:45:06,237 --> 00:45:07,970
 And cartoonists were rebelling.

953
00:45:07,972 --> 00:45:10,273
     It was getting tougher
           and tougher

954
00:45:10,275 --> 00:45:13,342
  To fit really quality content
        into the strips.

955
00:45:13,344 --> 00:45:16,045
      -I typically avoided
     looking at comic pages

956
00:45:16,047 --> 00:45:19,716
       Because I so hated
   how mine looked on a page.

957
00:45:19,718 --> 00:45:22,852
  Your strips look so beautiful
        as they head out.

958
00:45:22,854 --> 00:45:25,988
     You know, you draw them
 this big, and they're gorgeous.

959
00:45:25,990 --> 00:45:29,192
  And you see them, especially
  25 years ago, 30 years ago,

960
00:45:29,194 --> 00:45:31,494
       Reproduced this big
        on bad newsprint,

961
00:45:31,496 --> 00:45:34,297
     Often out of alignment,
     and it was depressing.

962
00:45:34,299 --> 00:45:36,933
          It was like,
  "why am I in this business?"

963
00:45:36,935 --> 00:45:39,769
    -The smaller and smaller
          reproductions

964
00:45:39,771 --> 00:45:42,472
   Meant there was less chance
          for visuals,

965
00:45:42,474 --> 00:45:44,941
    Less chance to draw well,

966
00:45:44,943 --> 00:45:48,077
  Less chance for the audience
          to appreciate

967
00:45:48,079 --> 00:45:51,180
          Good drawing
    and imaginative visuals.

968
00:45:51,182 --> 00:45:56,185
       If you are working
   to create a graphic entity,

969
00:45:56,187 --> 00:45:59,889
   A pictorial representation
          of something,

970
00:45:59,891 --> 00:46:02,959
    You don't want to see it
 shrunk down to a postage stamp.

971
00:46:02,961 --> 00:46:06,262
 -Some of the first comic strips
 in america in the early 1900s,

972
00:46:06,264 --> 00:46:08,531
          Some of those
   were like full-page comics.

973
00:46:08,533 --> 00:46:11,968
  And, like, those artists had
just huge palettes to work with,

974
00:46:11,970 --> 00:46:14,270
           And the art
  was really, really important.

975
00:46:14,272 --> 00:46:16,873
    Whereas now, some people
  are working with, like, this,

976
00:46:16,875 --> 00:46:18,808
    And it's black-and-white,

977
00:46:18,810 --> 00:46:21,244
         And everything
 is about the simplicity of it.

978
00:46:21,246 --> 00:46:23,312
            -Clearly,
  his focus was on the sundays.

979
00:46:23,314 --> 00:46:24,847
  So he approached the sundays

980
00:46:24,849 --> 00:46:27,016
        As an opportunity
    to do some dynamite art,

981
00:46:27,018 --> 00:46:30,253
  Which in the comics, has been
   a dying thing for decades.

982
00:46:30,255 --> 00:46:33,122
    -You almost cry a little
when you look at the old comics,

983
00:46:33,124 --> 00:46:35,858
    When they had a full page
   to do whatever they wanted.

984
00:46:35,860 --> 00:46:38,060
        You know, again,
   the "nemo" in slumberland,

985
00:46:38,062 --> 00:46:40,163
      I mean, good heavens,
       it was just unreal.

986
00:46:40,165 --> 00:46:43,366
        -When you look at
  the great strips of the past,

987
00:46:43,368 --> 00:46:49,438
   Not only mccay and herriman
 and milt caniff and walt kelly,

988
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:52,208
      The general standard
        of draftsmanship

989
00:46:52,210 --> 00:46:53,943
     Used to be much higher.

990
00:46:53,945 --> 00:46:56,412
        You couldn't have
     "terry and the pirates"

991
00:46:56,414 --> 00:46:59,982
      The same way you did
      in the '30s and '40s.

992
00:46:59,984 --> 00:47:03,386
  -The biggest and most popular
  strips were the story strips.

993
00:47:03,388 --> 00:47:07,590
     They needed that space
    to move the story along.

994
00:47:07,592 --> 00:47:12,028
Well, as they shrunk the comics,
there wasn't that space anymore

995
00:47:12,030 --> 00:47:14,430
        For both the art
        and the dialogue.

996
00:47:14,432 --> 00:47:18,868
 -Bill's particular problem was
 that, with the Sunday format,

997
00:47:18,870 --> 00:47:22,171
     It could be chopped up
    to fit different sizes --

998
00:47:22,173 --> 00:47:26,609
Either a half page or a third of
a page or a quarter of a page --

999
00:47:26,611 --> 00:47:29,178
           And he felt
     trying to configure it

1000
00:47:29,180 --> 00:47:31,614
         So that it fit
      into all those sizes

1001
00:47:31,616 --> 00:47:35,084
           Was really
     an obstruction for him.

1002
00:47:35,086 --> 00:47:38,454
 So he came back with one-sized
   proposal, and that was it.

1003
00:47:38,456 --> 00:47:41,891
 -Once the sundays were totally
     in watterson's control,

1004
00:47:41,893 --> 00:47:44,293
  They didn't get moved around
         or chopped up,

1005
00:47:44,295 --> 00:47:46,362
        Or they wouldn't
        lose the top bar.

1006
00:47:46,364 --> 00:47:49,031
      That really opened up
       a whole new world,

1007
00:47:49,033 --> 00:47:52,401
  In the sense that the artwork
   could go to another level,

1008
00:47:52,403 --> 00:47:55,438
     Because he was working
   with a really huge palette

1009
00:47:55,440 --> 00:47:58,908
   Where it was uninterrupted,
     unbreakable half pages.

1010
00:47:58,910 --> 00:48:00,443
    That was amazing to watch

1011
00:48:00,445 --> 00:48:03,379
  Because it really allowed him
        to work in a way

1012
00:48:03,381 --> 00:48:06,382
       That just freed up
         his creativity.

1013
00:48:06,384 --> 00:48:10,253
       -Every three years
    at ohio state university,

1014
00:48:10,255 --> 00:48:12,588
  The cartoon library & museum

1015
00:48:12,590 --> 00:48:15,324
              Hosts
  the festival of cartoon art,

1016
00:48:15,326 --> 00:48:19,095
 Which brings together scholars,
       cartoonists, fans,

1017
00:48:19,097 --> 00:48:21,964
   And industry professionals
      from around the world

1018
00:48:21,966 --> 00:48:25,234
   To celebrate comic creators
         and their work.

1019
00:48:25,236 --> 00:48:27,937
     In 1989, bill watterson

1020
00:48:27,939 --> 00:48:30,273
     Was a featured speaker
        at the festival,

1021
00:48:30,275 --> 00:48:32,141
   And he took the opportunity

1022
00:48:32,143 --> 00:48:35,411
     To talk about the power
   and possibilities of comics

1023
00:48:35,413 --> 00:48:38,281
   And how the current climate
         for cartoonists

1024
00:48:38,283 --> 00:48:40,917
    Was failing the art form.

1025
00:48:40,919 --> 00:48:43,219
    -He gave a speech titled
 "the cheapening of the comics,"

1026
00:48:43,221 --> 00:48:47,023
    Which was really his way
  of drawing a line in the sand

1027
00:48:47,025 --> 00:48:49,692
     And saying, "if we are
to take this art form seriously,

1028
00:48:49,694 --> 00:48:51,227
   If we are to serve it best,

1029
00:48:51,229 --> 00:48:53,329
      These are the things
      that we should do."

1030
00:48:53,331 --> 00:48:56,365
 And it was sort of a series of
 seven or eight or nine points

1031
00:48:56,367 --> 00:48:58,167
           That says,

1032
00:48:58,169 --> 00:48:59,969
  "look, you cheapen the comics
   when you commercialize it.

1033
00:48:59,971 --> 00:49:02,405
You cheapen the comics when you
take the artist of the equation.

1034
00:49:02,407 --> 00:49:04,941
     You cheapen the comics
     when you let it go on

1035
00:49:04,943 --> 00:49:08,110
          A life beyond
  what it was intended to do."

1036
00:49:08,112 --> 00:49:10,079
     "you cheapen the comics
  when you give the syndicate,"

1037
00:49:10,081 --> 00:49:12,581
 Which is the publisher and the
 distributor, "too much power."

1038
00:49:12,583 --> 00:49:14,951
         "and if we are
  to truly serve this art form,

1039
00:49:14,953 --> 00:49:17,620
 The artist has to come first,
 their voice has to come first,

1040
00:49:17,622 --> 00:49:20,089
   And the art before commerce
       has to come first."

1041
00:49:20,091 --> 00:49:22,224
       He was essentially
   throwing down the gauntlet

1042
00:49:22,226 --> 00:49:24,126
        And said, "look,
      we've lost something

1043
00:49:24,128 --> 00:49:26,128
      "from the early part
      of the 20th century,

1044
00:49:26,130 --> 00:49:28,597
   "where, you know, the art
   was beautifully displayed,

1045
00:49:28,599 --> 00:49:31,100
    "the artists were given
    this truly unique voice,

1046
00:49:31,102 --> 00:49:33,536
     "and we need to go back
      to a different time,

1047
00:49:33,538 --> 00:49:35,571
       To a different way
         of cartooning."

1048
00:49:35,573 --> 00:49:39,308
 -I think he took a very lofty,
at times even philosophical look

1049
00:49:39,310 --> 00:49:41,077
        At the art form.

1050
00:49:41,079 --> 00:49:42,545
There's nothing wrong with that,

1051
00:49:42,547 --> 00:49:45,014
     Because he held himself
     to those own standards,

1052
00:49:45,016 --> 00:49:47,416
   And I have a lot of respect
     for him for doing that.

1053
00:49:47,418 --> 00:49:49,352
            -I think
  it was kind of a brave speech

1054
00:49:49,354 --> 00:49:51,087
       Because mort walker
   took it very personally --

1055
00:49:51,089 --> 00:49:52,989
   Of "beetle bailey" fame --

1056
00:49:52,991 --> 00:49:55,624
 And a few other bigger names in
 cartooning took it personally,

1057
00:49:55,626 --> 00:49:58,027
     Because they viewed it
    as a shot across the bow

1058
00:49:58,029 --> 00:49:59,729
           Of the way
  they handled their business,

1059
00:49:59,731 --> 00:50:01,630
      The way they handled
        their cartooning.

1060
00:50:01,632 --> 00:50:05,034
       -Within the crowd,
       my recollection was

1061
00:50:05,036 --> 00:50:11,374
  That there was a strong split
      among those who were,

1062
00:50:11,376 --> 00:50:14,110
       "yeah, go get them.
   Go tell them the way it is"

1063
00:50:14,112 --> 00:50:16,345
      And the other side,
      which was, you know,

1064
00:50:16,347 --> 00:50:18,714
        "who is this kid
   to tell me how to do my art

1065
00:50:18,716 --> 00:50:21,484
       And do what I want
 with my life and my business?"

1066
00:50:21,486 --> 00:50:24,353
  -Watterson was coming out of
 more of the artistic tradition

1067
00:50:24,355 --> 00:50:26,522
        And just, "look,
   we can raise this art up."

1068
00:50:26,524 --> 00:50:29,225
  And others were coming from,
    "look, it has always been

1069
00:50:29,227 --> 00:50:31,260
        This intersection
      of art and commerce,

1070
00:50:31,262 --> 00:50:33,029
    So you cannot deny that."

1071
00:50:33,031 --> 00:50:35,297
    You know, I've talked to
 jeff smith of "bone" about it,

1072
00:50:35,299 --> 00:50:38,434
 And he said he literally walked
   out of that hall and said,

1073
00:50:38,436 --> 00:50:41,570
"I realize that 'bone' cannot be
      what I want it to be

1074
00:50:41,572 --> 00:50:43,072
     In a comic-strip form.

1075
00:50:43,074 --> 00:50:44,640
  I have to forge my own path.

1076
00:50:44,642 --> 00:50:47,043
      I have to take 'bone'
           elsewhere."

1077
00:50:53,150 --> 00:50:56,452
   -My relationship with bill
       was one of letters.

1078
00:50:56,454 --> 00:50:59,388
       And it's not unique
         to cartoonists

1079
00:50:59,390 --> 00:51:02,258
          That we draw
  in our letters to each other.

1080
00:51:02,260 --> 00:51:04,693
  But it's unique that he would

1081
00:51:04,695 --> 00:51:07,596
  Spend as much time as he did
        on his drawings,

1082
00:51:07,598 --> 00:51:09,365
     Which is just like him.

1083
00:51:09,367 --> 00:51:11,534
      He didn't do anything
           like I did,

1084
00:51:11,536 --> 00:51:13,736
            Which was
    by the seat of the pants

1085
00:51:13,738 --> 00:51:15,638
     And extremely quickly.

1086
00:51:15,640 --> 00:51:17,440
The source of much of the energy

1087
00:51:17,442 --> 00:51:19,442
        With the letters
        and the drawings,

1088
00:51:19,444 --> 00:51:23,446
    To me, was at my expense.

1089
00:51:23,448 --> 00:51:25,581
            He and I
    were the yin and the yang

1090
00:51:25,583 --> 00:51:27,450
Of the comic strips in the '80s,

1091
00:51:27,452 --> 00:51:33,355
   Because I was making these,
         and he was not.

1092
00:51:33,357 --> 00:51:36,592
    And as he would draw me,

1093
00:51:36,594 --> 00:51:39,462
     I was taking the money
   and buying gasoline with it

1094
00:51:39,464 --> 00:51:41,497
         And pumping it
       into my speedboat,

1095
00:51:41,499 --> 00:51:43,232
        Which he used to
        put on the bottom

1096
00:51:43,234 --> 00:51:45,234
  Almost of each of the letters
          he wrote me.

1097
00:51:45,236 --> 00:51:48,604
  And the person handing me the
  money was the syndicate boss,

1098
00:51:48,606 --> 00:51:50,539
 Who he had no appreciation for.

1099
00:51:50,541 --> 00:51:54,243
  So that's how he saw me, and
 it's how he saw the syndicate,

1100
00:51:54,245 --> 00:51:57,546
    And that's how he saw the
exploitation of one's characters

1101
00:51:57,548 --> 00:51:58,848
        In a comic strip,

1102
00:51:58,850 --> 00:52:02,418
     All nicely personified
         in one drawing.

1103
00:52:02,420 --> 00:52:04,386
          -We realized
    that "calvin and hobbes"

1104
00:52:04,388 --> 00:52:05,788
 Was gonna be huge in licensing.

1105
00:52:05,790 --> 00:52:07,590
    'cause we could just tell
          by the signs,

1106
00:52:07,592 --> 00:52:09,391
  The response from the public.

1107
00:52:09,393 --> 00:52:12,661
  But bill made it clear that
  he was just not gonna do it.

1108
00:52:12,663 --> 00:52:15,698
     -Watterson, obviously,
    had very strong feelings

1109
00:52:15,700 --> 00:52:20,769
       About merchandising
and the commerce side of comics.

1110
00:52:20,771 --> 00:52:23,205
             I mean,
    he participated in a way,

1111
00:52:23,207 --> 00:52:27,176
   Just being in a newspaper,
        as part of that.

1112
00:52:27,178 --> 00:52:30,179
       But he clearly had
       very specific ideas

1113
00:52:30,181 --> 00:52:34,884
     About how merchandising
    can change the characters

1114
00:52:34,886 --> 00:52:36,485
        Or change the art

1115
00:52:36,487 --> 00:52:40,256
      Or change the creator
    and what their vision is.

1116
00:52:40,258 --> 00:52:42,591
     -The idea of, you know,

1117
00:52:42,593 --> 00:52:45,761
        A stuffed hobbes
  sitting on a shelf somewhere

1118
00:52:45,763 --> 00:52:47,830
         Would basically
      answer that question

1119
00:52:47,832 --> 00:52:50,232
          That's always
    hanging over the strip --

1120
00:52:50,234 --> 00:52:52,768
    You know, is hobbes real?
      Is he a stuffed toy?

1121
00:52:52,770 --> 00:52:55,204
  Well, there's a stuffed toy,
            you know?

1122
00:52:55,206 --> 00:52:57,439
          -We have seen
   many comic-strip characters

1123
00:52:57,441 --> 00:53:00,342
    Go from being, you know,
  figures you see in the paper

1124
00:53:00,344 --> 00:53:01,710
   That may give you a laugh,

1125
00:53:01,712 --> 00:53:03,712
        To being kind of
        a national blight

1126
00:53:03,714 --> 00:53:06,315
           In the case
   of something like garfield,

1127
00:53:06,317 --> 00:53:09,251
   That at one point was on, I
think, 5,000 different products.

1128
00:53:09,253 --> 00:53:12,288
       And the character
       becomes ubiquitous

1129
00:53:12,290 --> 00:53:15,958
 And begins to feel like a pest
 or something you can't escape,

1130
00:53:15,960 --> 00:53:19,562
    Rather than something you
  look forward to encountering.

1131
00:53:19,564 --> 00:53:22,498
          In a society
    that is as media-obsessed

1132
00:53:22,500 --> 00:53:25,668
       And money-obsessed
    as ours is and was then,

1133
00:53:25,670 --> 00:53:29,738
  His decision seemed strange,
   if not almost un-american.

1134
00:53:29,740 --> 00:53:33,909
  He walked away from literally
   tens of millions of dollars

1135
00:53:33,911 --> 00:53:35,444
        In merchandising,

1136
00:53:35,446 --> 00:53:37,846
       Because everything
       that snoopy was on,

1137
00:53:37,848 --> 00:53:40,316
     I'm sure he was offered
           for hobbes.

1138
00:53:40,318 --> 00:53:42,818
  -"sparky" did feel protective

1139
00:53:42,820 --> 00:53:46,488
     About being criticized
         for licensing,

1140
00:53:46,490 --> 00:53:47,923
        Because he said,

1141
00:53:47,925 --> 00:53:51,360
"people don't realize, you know,
       how it all started

1142
00:53:51,362 --> 00:53:53,963
       And that everything
   was somebody coming to me,

1143
00:53:53,965 --> 00:53:56,298
 Wanting to use the characters.

1144
00:53:56,300 --> 00:53:57,733
      I drew it for them."

1145
00:53:57,735 --> 00:54:00,536
      And it had an aspect
         of kind of fun,

1146
00:54:00,538 --> 00:54:02,638
 An entrepreneurialism about it

1147
00:54:02,640 --> 00:54:04,940
       That was not to do
         with business.

1148
00:54:04,942 --> 00:54:08,844
        It was to do with
       extending your art,

1149
00:54:08,846 --> 00:54:11,513
   Extending your sentiments.

1150
00:54:11,515 --> 00:54:14,984
 -When "sparky" did what he did,
    "sparky" had no template,

1151
00:54:14,986 --> 00:54:17,519
      And I'm talking about
         the licensing.

