01:04:40,911 --> 01:04:44,512
   They love him as a writer.
 They respect him as an artist.

1382
01:04:44,514 --> 01:04:46,615
  And those are the two people

1383
01:04:46,617 --> 01:04:49,050
       That I was chasing
       at the same time.

1384
01:04:49,052 --> 01:04:52,287
  You know, there was somebody
 who was incredibly principled,

1385
01:04:52,289 --> 01:04:53,955
        Who stuck to it,

1386
01:04:53,957 --> 01:04:56,124
      And who also happened
   to be incredibly talented.

1387
01:04:56,126 --> 01:04:58,526
 And then there was a guy that,
   like, really turns his back

1388
01:04:58,528 --> 01:05:01,296
          On this whole
     public-persona machine

1389
01:05:01,298 --> 01:05:03,899
    That we've come to expect
          as americans.

1390
01:05:03,901 --> 01:05:05,567
               So,
 over the course of the journey,

1391
01:05:05,569 --> 01:05:08,103
    I was rooting for the guy
     that was so principled,

1392
01:05:08,105 --> 01:05:10,205
 And yet I was peeved at the guy

1393
01:05:10,207 --> 01:05:12,974
     That was not giving me
         what I wanted.

1394
01:05:12,976 --> 01:05:16,111
       It was frustrating,
   and yet, at the same time,

1395
01:05:16,113 --> 01:05:18,446
         I couldn't help
        but root for him.

1396
01:05:18,448 --> 01:05:21,383
        You know, I think
   that he made his decisions,

1397
01:05:21,385 --> 01:05:23,518
   And I totally respect them.

1398
01:05:23,520 --> 01:05:26,288
     And any personal wants
      that I have from him

1399
01:05:26,290 --> 01:05:28,623
    Are selfishly motivated,

1400
01:05:28,625 --> 01:05:31,192
    And so that's up to him.

1401
01:05:48,311 --> 01:05:52,314
 -I would say my favorite strips
         are on my arm.

1402
01:05:52,316 --> 01:05:54,649
 I made sure I got some snowmen
            in there,

1403
01:05:54,651 --> 01:05:57,185
      Making fun of girls,
         the silly ones,

1404
01:05:57,187 --> 01:05:59,321
 Some of the imagination stuff,
         where he thinks

1405
01:05:59,323 --> 01:06:01,423
     He's a crocodile here,
     and he's just swimming.

1406
01:06:01,425 --> 01:06:04,693
  I try to get a little bit of
  everything -- stupendous man.

1407
01:06:04,695 --> 01:06:07,128
 When I was getting this tattoo,

1408
01:06:07,130 --> 01:06:09,331
          I knew a guy
  that could get phone numbers,

1409
01:06:09,333 --> 01:06:11,433
            And I got
 bill watterson's phone number.

1410
01:06:11,435 --> 01:06:13,702
   I wanted to get permission
        to get the tattoo

1411
01:06:13,704 --> 01:06:16,304
  So I wouldn't be just as bad
       as the bootleggers.

1412
01:06:16,306 --> 01:06:21,076
       But [clears throat]
he didn't return my phone calls.

1413
01:06:21,078 --> 01:06:23,011
      I did get it anyway.

1414
01:06:23,013 --> 01:06:26,081
         But I feel like
       it's not a bootleg.

1415
01:06:26,083 --> 01:06:28,316
   It's just a labor of love.

1416
01:06:28,318 --> 01:06:32,187
   [ up-tempo bluegrass music
             plays ]

1417
01:07:58,441 --> 01:08:02,077
     [ cheers and applause ]

1418
01:08:03,379 --> 01:08:06,681
       -People talk about
 kind of the death of cartooning

1419
01:08:06,683 --> 01:08:09,851
      Because of, kind of,
   the passing of newspapers.

1420
01:08:09,853 --> 01:08:12,087
          But, really,
    we're in a time right now

1421
01:08:12,089 --> 01:08:14,289
 Where it's not just newspapers.
           It's media.

1422
01:08:14,291 --> 01:08:15,723
    Like, media is changing,

1423
01:08:15,725 --> 01:08:18,726
    And the way we make money
     from media is changing.

1424
01:08:18,728 --> 01:08:21,563
 Newspaper comics are especially
      interesting, though,

1425
01:08:21,565 --> 01:08:24,599
Because they used to be unified.

1426
01:08:24,601 --> 01:08:27,202
 Like, every day, you'd open up,
    and your paper would have

1427
01:08:27,204 --> 01:08:30,171
        One or two pages
  devoted to newspaper comics.

1428
01:08:30,173 --> 01:08:32,340
 And, first of all, those pages

1429
01:08:32,342 --> 01:08:35,777
 Are getting cut down and shrunk
  more and more as time goes on

1430
01:08:35,779 --> 01:08:38,613
    And as newspaper budgets
        keep getting cut.

1431
01:08:38,615 --> 01:08:42,517
So you're not coming to the same
   collective space every day

1432
01:08:42,519 --> 01:08:45,286
   To experience the newspaper
           and comics.

1433
01:08:45,288 --> 01:08:47,455
  You know, you can go online,
      if you're interested,

1434
01:08:47,457 --> 01:08:50,125
   And either find the strips
      that you already like

1435
01:08:50,127 --> 01:08:51,392
    Or go discover new ones,

1436
01:08:51,394 --> 01:08:53,394
          But it's not
     the kind of same thing.

1437
01:08:53,396 --> 01:08:55,296
   You have to go to one page
           on gocomics

1438
01:08:55,298 --> 01:08:56,865
    For "calvin and hobbes,"

1439
01:08:56,867 --> 01:08:59,134
   And then you go to another
  independent artist's website

1440
01:08:59,136 --> 01:09:00,735
      For their web comic,

1441
01:09:00,737 --> 01:09:03,872
   And then you go to another
 website for another web comic.

1442
01:09:03,874 --> 01:09:06,274
 And, you know, you're surfing.

1443
01:09:06,276 --> 01:09:07,842
        But you're never
       going to one place

1444
01:09:07,844 --> 01:09:09,744
        To get all those
     different perspectives.

1445
01:09:09,746 --> 01:09:11,713
   And that was the cool thing
          about comics.

1446
01:09:11,715 --> 01:09:14,182
  Whether you liked "garfield"
       or "family circus"

1447
01:09:14,184 --> 01:09:16,384
      Or the "wizard of id"
     or "calvin and hobbes,"

1448
01:09:16,386 --> 01:09:18,520
   You could come to one page
        in the newspaper

1449
01:09:18,522 --> 01:09:20,288
    And experience them all.

1450
01:09:20,290 --> 01:09:23,825
     And because that medium
  is disappearing or shrinking,

1451
01:09:23,827 --> 01:09:26,461
That experience is disappearing,
            as well.

1452
01:09:26,463 --> 01:09:30,498
 -There is sort of a high point
   for mass distributed arts,

1453
01:09:30,500 --> 01:09:33,168
        Somewhere between
         the postwar era

1454
01:09:33,170 --> 01:09:35,904
     And probably somewhere
        in the mid '90s.

1455
01:09:35,906 --> 01:09:41,509
  And it's been a diminishment
 for tv, for films, for albums,

1456
01:09:41,511 --> 01:09:44,212
   For cartooning, for novels
        ever since then.

1457
01:09:44,214 --> 01:09:46,915
   Because the basic fact is,
          as a culture,

1458
01:09:46,917 --> 01:09:50,552
   The means of distribution
   have been so filtered out,

1459
01:09:50,554 --> 01:09:53,288
    And the means of creation
    have been so filtered out

1460
01:09:53,290 --> 01:09:55,790
     That we're now getting
   tens of thousands of blogs,

1461
01:09:55,792 --> 01:09:57,892
Tens of thousands of web comics,
tens of thousands of small bands

1462
01:09:57,894 --> 01:09:59,727
  That can distribute directly.

1463
01:09:59,729 --> 01:10:03,932
   -There simply is no way to
 concentrate people's attention,

1464
01:10:03,934 --> 01:10:07,368
  And when it gets concentrated
          on something,

1465
01:10:07,370 --> 01:10:09,904
    It gets concentrated for
  a very short period of time,

1466
01:10:09,906 --> 01:10:11,739
    Probably very intensely.

1467
01:10:11,741 --> 01:10:15,543
 Everybody is tweeting about it
   and watching it on youtube,

1468
01:10:15,545 --> 01:10:19,347
   And then it's gone, because
 the next thing has come along.

1469
01:10:19,349 --> 01:10:21,316
         -You're getting
 all of these incredible voices

1470
01:10:21,318 --> 01:10:22,917
         That you never
    would have gotten before,

1471
01:10:22,919 --> 01:10:25,386
  But you no longer have those
  water-cooler pieces of art,

1472
01:10:25,388 --> 01:10:26,654
   Where everyone would know,

1473
01:10:26,656 --> 01:10:27,922
         Everyone would
      gather around at work

1474
01:10:27,924 --> 01:10:29,624
       And say, "ah. Yeah.
        That's the one."

1475
01:10:29,626 --> 01:10:34,462
  -There will no longer ever be
    a, like, rolling stones.

1476
01:10:34,464 --> 01:10:36,798
   There won't be the beatles.

1477
01:10:36,800 --> 01:10:39,400
         There won't be
        an elvis presley

1478
01:10:39,402 --> 01:10:42,704
 For the same reason there won't
 be another "calvin and hobbes."

1479
01:10:42,706 --> 01:10:47,609
   The market is digitalizing,
       and it's atomizing.

1480
01:10:47,611 --> 01:10:52,347
    So it's being spread over
       a far wider surface

1481
01:10:52,349 --> 01:10:55,250
  But in a much thinner layer.

1482
01:10:55,252 --> 01:10:56,751
   -If the "far side" started,

1483
01:10:56,753 --> 01:10:59,487
     Or "calvin and hobbes"
  started today in newspapers,

1484
01:10:59,489 --> 01:11:01,823
   It would probably do well,

1485
01:11:01,825 --> 01:11:04,759
        But I don't think
    it would have the impact

1486
01:11:04,761 --> 01:11:06,928
  That it had in the late '80s.

1487
01:11:06,930 --> 01:11:09,397
       -If you can name me
       a cartoon character

1488
01:11:09,399 --> 01:11:15,303
That's been invented since 1985,
          that's new --

1489
01:11:15,305 --> 01:11:19,841
        From comic page,
      not on television --

1490
01:11:19,843 --> 01:11:22,343
       If you can name me
       a cartoon character

1491
01:11:22,345 --> 01:11:24,746
    That is a household term
            or a name

1492
01:11:24,748 --> 01:11:26,781
 Throughout this country, truly,

1493
01:11:26,783 --> 01:11:29,484
    That my mother would know
      and that I would know

1494
01:11:29,486 --> 01:11:31,319
   And that my kids would know

1495
01:11:31,321 --> 01:11:33,755
    And anyone through canada
           would know,

1496
01:11:33,757 --> 01:11:35,456
    I would be very shocked.

1497
01:11:35,458 --> 01:11:38,493
        And I don't think
    it's gonna happen again.

1498
01:11:38,495 --> 01:11:39,894
  So I think calvin and hobbes

1499
01:11:39,896 --> 01:11:41,996
       Are the last great
       cartoon characters.

1500
01:11:41,998 --> 01:11:43,765
       So he nailed that.

1501
01:11:43,767 --> 01:11:47,669
     It's great to be first,
 but it's also good to be last.

1502
01:11:47,671 --> 01:11:49,537
      -"calvin and hobbes"
         was of its age,

1503
01:11:49,539 --> 01:11:51,906
 And you couldn't transplant it
      elsewhere, you know?

1504
01:11:51,908 --> 01:11:53,641
        And, thankfully,
       it <i>was</i> of its age,

1505
01:11:53,643 --> 01:11:55,443
      Which is another way
        of looking at it.

1506
01:11:55,445 --> 01:11:57,512
  Thank god that it <i>did</i> appear
        when it appeared,

1507
01:11:57,514 --> 01:12:00,882
  And thank god that it <i>did</i> run
  when it ran and where it ran,

1508
01:12:00,884 --> 01:12:04,385
 Because I don't think it would
   have been near the success,

1509
01:12:04,387 --> 01:12:07,822
  Artistically or financially,
     for its worthy creator

1510
01:12:07,824 --> 01:12:10,625
   Had it run any other time,

1511
01:12:10,627 --> 01:12:13,494
  Which is both sort of amazing
        and kind of sad,

1512
01:12:13,496 --> 01:12:15,563
       In a way, you know?

1513
01:12:33,449 --> 01:12:37,485
     -If you were to ask me
   the question 10 years ago,

1514
01:12:37,487 --> 01:12:41,622
"how would his lack of licensing
       affect the strip,"

1515
01:12:41,624 --> 01:12:44,992
       I would have said,
       "it's ridiculous.
       It's gonna fail.

1516
01:12:44,994 --> 01:12:47,362
         It's gonna hurt
      the long-term legacy.

1517
01:12:47,364 --> 01:12:49,597
  People will forget the strip
            quickly."

1518
01:12:49,599 --> 01:12:52,533
       Because, you know,
part of snoopy's enduring legacy

1519
01:12:52,535 --> 01:12:56,404
     Is that your 4-year-old
     can have a plush snoopy

1520
01:12:56,406 --> 01:12:59,107
      And then learn about
   the cartoons and the strip.

1521
01:12:59,109 --> 01:13:01,843
        They fall in love
  with the merchandising first

1522
01:13:01,845 --> 01:13:05,847
     And then the characters
  and the content and the art.

1523
01:13:05,849 --> 01:13:08,015
      So I would have said,
     "it's never gonna work.

1524
01:13:08,017 --> 01:13:10,952
 "the strip is gonna go, vanish.
 We'll never hear from it again.

1525
01:13:10,954 --> 01:13:13,821
    "and there will be people
   like me, 40 years from now,

1526
01:13:13,823 --> 01:13:15,890
       "talking about it
       the same way we do

1527
01:13:15,892 --> 01:13:18,793
"about 'krazy kat' and 'pogo' --
      brilliant, wonderful.

1528
01:13:18,795 --> 01:13:20,528
 The public has forgotten them."

1529
01:13:20,530 --> 01:13:23,598
  Not with "calvin and hobbes."
         it's universal.

1530
01:13:23,600 --> 01:13:26,768
  It has maintained its quality
          and integrity

1531
01:13:26,770 --> 01:13:30,705
  To the point that kids today
 coming up are still reading it.

1532
01:13:30,707 --> 01:13:34,475
  How did they learn about it?
 It's in their school libraries.

1533
01:13:34,477 --> 01:13:36,744
            That was
    one of the breakthroughs,

1534
01:13:36,746 --> 01:13:40,882
   Is that "calvin and hobbes"
 was <i>encouraged</i> by the teachers.

1535
01:13:40,884 --> 01:13:43,918
   Teachers spotted the child
         who was calvin

1536
01:13:43,920 --> 01:13:47,655
    And said, "you're calvin.
    I want you to read this."

1537
01:13:47,657 --> 01:13:50,958
    And it got them reading.
 And parents encouraged it, too.

1538
01:13:50,960 --> 01:13:54,562
  So I think that that made up
 for a lot of the merchandising

1539
01:13:54,564 --> 01:13:56,898
     That would have helped
          carry it on.

1540
01:13:56,900 --> 01:14:00,168
 That made up for the animation
      that never happened,

1541
01:14:00,170 --> 01:14:03,037
       Is that the comic
       was just that good

1542
01:14:03,039 --> 01:14:05,740
      That it could survive
           without it.

1543
01:14:05,742 --> 01:14:09,076
        I don't know that
    there is a lot like that.

1544
01:14:09,078 --> 01:14:12,847
 -I've lost track of the number
      of 6- and 7-year-olds

1545
01:14:12,849 --> 01:14:16,984
  Who list "calvin and hobbes"
 as their favorite comic strip.

1546
01:14:16,986 --> 01:14:19,720
       And they know about
       the transmogrifier,

1547
01:14:19,722 --> 01:14:21,989
         They know about
        the time machine,

1548
01:14:21,991 --> 01:14:23,558
      And they know how to

1549
01:14:23,560 --> 01:14:26,561
      Turn a cardboard box
    into absolutely anything.

1550
01:14:26,563 --> 01:14:29,964
     I think there's even a
 generation of kids named calvin

1551
01:14:29,966 --> 01:14:34,469
      Because people my age
 are starting to become parents.

1552
01:14:34,471 --> 01:14:39,740
    And all it takes, really,
  is seeing that dog-eared copy

1553
01:14:39,742 --> 01:14:43,578
   Of "something under the bed
   is drooling" or "yukon ho!"

1554
01:14:43,580 --> 01:14:47,181
     At your public library
  or on your school bookshelf.

1555
01:14:47,183 --> 01:14:50,551
-I've heard questions like, "why
are people still reading that?"

1556
01:14:50,553 --> 01:14:52,653
      Or "why are the books
       still so popular?"

1557
01:14:52,655 --> 01:14:54,222
      You know, "he hasn't
 been in newspapers in 15 years.

1558
01:14:54,224 --> 01:14:55,790
         Why are people
    still talking about him?"

1559
01:14:55,792 --> 01:14:58,559
         And it's like,
   "'cause it's transcendent."

1560
01:14:58,561 --> 01:14:59,961
    That's the beauty of it.

1561
01:14:59,963 --> 01:15:01,529
      And that's, I think,

1562
01:15:01,531 --> 01:15:04,532
    Why calvin will be around
    10 years from today, 25,

1563
01:15:04,534 --> 01:15:07,535
     Because he talks to us
        on a deeper level

1564
01:15:07,537 --> 01:15:09,704
     Than just a punch line.

1565
01:15:09,706 --> 01:15:11,539
     -It's kind of reflected
           in the fact

1566
01:15:11,541 --> 01:15:13,741
     That people can go back
     to "calvin and hobbes"

1567
01:15:13,743 --> 01:15:15,910
   And read them over and over
    and over and over again,

1568
01:15:15,912 --> 01:15:17,545
   And they're always joyful.

1569
01:15:17,547 --> 01:15:19,647
       Even when you know
what the punch line is gonna be,

1570
01:15:19,649 --> 01:15:21,249
        It's still funny.
          [ chuckles ]

1571
01:15:21,251 --> 01:15:24,886
  -I feel inspired when I read
  a "calvin and hobbes" strip.

1572
01:15:24,888 --> 01:15:27,288
   You know, as a human being,
         I'm just like,

1573
01:15:27,290 --> 01:15:29,156
"calvin's enjoying life so much.

1574
01:15:29,158 --> 01:15:31,759
        I want to go out
    and enjoy life that way."

1575
01:15:31,761 --> 01:15:36,931
  -It can't really be contained
       by print or panels.

1576
01:15:36,933 --> 01:15:42,537
 It's a living, breathing thing,
 and I think it always will be.

1577
01:15:42,539 --> 01:15:45,806
     He used ink and brushes
      and some watercolors,

1578
01:15:45,808 --> 01:15:48,910
         But, you know,
   he created life with that,

1579
01:15:48,912 --> 01:15:53,781
      Which I think is what
  every cartoonist aspires to,

1580
01:15:53,783 --> 01:15:56,918
       But not many of us
     ever get to achieve it.

1581
01:15:56,920 --> 01:16:01,889
-"calvin and hobbes" -- there is
   not a single element in it

1582
01:16:01,891 --> 01:16:05,059
  That isn't kind of as current
   as it was when it came out.

1583
01:16:05,061 --> 01:16:08,829
   It's all about being a kid.
   It's all about imagination.

1584
01:16:08,831 --> 01:16:11,232
Every single thing's referenced.

1585
01:16:11,234 --> 01:16:13,668
     I don't have to explain
     the context to my kids.

1586
01:16:13,670 --> 01:16:15,803
     They actually live it
     in the same way I did.

1587
01:16:15,805 --> 01:16:17,872
       It's not changing.

1588
01:16:17,874 --> 01:16:19,640
         And, you know,
      to read "doonesbury"

1589
01:16:19,642 --> 01:16:21,876
    Or to read "bloom county"
     or the other, you know,

1590
01:16:21,878 --> 01:16:23,945
   For me, the most important
       things growing up,

1591
01:16:23,947 --> 01:16:25,880
        You need to have
     a sense of the history.

1592
01:16:25,882 --> 01:16:28,282
     You need to understand
   the pop culture of the time

1593
01:16:28,284 --> 01:16:30,585
     In a very specific way.

1594
01:16:30,587 --> 01:16:32,286
     And "calvin and hobbes"

1595
01:16:32,288 --> 01:16:35,056
      Just kind of requires
       that you're alive.

1596
01:16:35,058 --> 01:16:39,126
          [ chuckles ]
 and it is quite an achievement.

1597
01:16:39,128 --> 01:16:40,861
 -You know, I've been fortunate

1598
01:16:40,863 --> 01:16:43,130
          To work with
   some wonderful cartoonists,

1599
01:16:43,132 --> 01:16:46,100
And, you know, certainly, at the
top of that list has to be bill,

1600
01:16:46,102 --> 01:16:49,236
  Because he was so different,
         so challenging.

1601
01:16:49,238 --> 01:16:53,240
He really caused us as a company
     and me as an individual

1602
01:16:53,242 --> 01:16:56,777
  To rethink the ways we dealt
         with cartoonist

1603
01:16:56,779 --> 01:16:58,980
And, you know, what our role was

1604
01:16:58,982 --> 01:17:02,717
 In helping them get their work
      out into the public.

1605
01:17:02,719 --> 01:17:07,822
         His creativity
  and the result of his efforts

1606
01:17:07,824 --> 01:17:10,691
    Were, you know, up there

1607
01:17:10,693 --> 01:17:12,627
 With probably the two or three
     or four greatest strips

1608
01:17:12,629 --> 01:17:13,961
          Of all time.

1609
01:17:13,963 --> 01:17:17,298
        I think "calvin"
  is something that will last.

1610
01:17:17,300 --> 01:17:18,933
       And, heaven forbid,

1611
01:17:18,935 --> 01:17:22,036
          If newspapers
   were to disappear tomorrow

1612
01:17:22,038 --> 01:17:24,171
            And books
     were not to be printed,

1613
01:17:24,173 --> 01:17:27,208
 There would be some way people
   would want to find his work

1614
01:17:27,210 --> 01:17:28,909
       And read it again,

1615
01:17:28,911 --> 01:17:30,778
Because I think it's that strong

1616
01:17:30,780 --> 01:17:32,980
        And that enduring
        and that special.

1617
01:17:39,655 --> 01:17:41,155
        -Over the years,

1618
01:17:41,157 --> 01:17:44,191
 My favorite "calvin and hobbes"
       strip has changed.

1619
01:17:44,193 --> 01:17:46,994
         When watterson
 was still writing and drawing,

1620
01:17:46,996 --> 01:17:48,929
My favorite might change weekly,

1621
01:17:48,931 --> 01:17:50,297
   Especially as he continued

1622
01:17:50,299 --> 01:17:52,099
           To put out
    some of his greatest work

1623
01:17:52,101 --> 01:17:53,801
     In the last few years.

1624
01:17:53,803 --> 01:17:56,270
      I have my collection
  of "calvin and hobbes" strips

1625
01:17:56,272 --> 01:17:58,973
           That I love
   for one reason or another.

1626
01:17:58,975 --> 01:18:01,108
   But looking back at it all,

1627
01:18:01,110 --> 01:18:03,744
        As much as I love
some of the strips for the humor

1628
01:18:03,746 --> 01:18:05,680
        Or the adventure
       or the amazing art

1629
01:18:05,682 --> 01:18:08,883
    Or the imaginative place
    that the strip took me,

1630
01:18:08,885 --> 01:18:11,252
            The strip
   that I can't really forget

1631
01:18:11,254 --> 01:18:13,988
    Is one that nobody else
    has ever mentioned to me

1632
01:18:13,990 --> 01:18:16,891
          As a favorite
     or even a notable one.

1633
01:18:16,893 --> 01:18:19,060
     When I've described it
         to other fans,

1634
01:18:19,062 --> 01:18:21,328
        I don't often get
     a look of recognition.

1635
01:18:21,330 --> 01:18:27,034
 But for me, it's unforgettable,
  and it has a special meaning.

1636
01:18:27,036 --> 01:18:29,770
  I'll never know exactly what
bill watterson's intentions were

1637
01:18:29,772 --> 01:18:31,238
        With this strip.

1638
01:18:31,240 --> 01:18:32,873
           I, myself,

1639
01:18:32,875 --> 01:18:35,109
     Can see a few different
    possible interpretations.

1640
01:18:35,111 --> 01:18:36,944
 But I can no longer look at it

1641
01:18:36,946 --> 01:18:39,380
      Without feeling like
I've glimpsed beyond the surface

1642
01:18:39,382 --> 01:18:42,183
        Of a comic strip
     filled with imagination

1643
01:18:42,185 --> 01:18:45,352
        And magic and joy
  and adventure and friendship

1644
01:18:45,354 --> 01:18:49,090
     And seen instead a hint
  of tremendous disappointment

1645
01:18:49,092 --> 01:18:51,892
            And loss.

1646
01:18:51,894 --> 01:18:54,161
       Watterson conceived
         of this strip.

1647
01:18:54,163 --> 01:18:56,464
      He wrote it, drew it,
          and inked it

1648
01:18:56,466 --> 01:18:58,766
              Using
    the simplest of tools --

1649
01:18:58,768 --> 01:19:04,238
   Bristol board, 2h pencils,
  a sable brush, and india ink.

1650
01:19:04,240 --> 01:19:06,407
        He handed it over
        to his syndicate

1651
01:19:06,409 --> 01:19:09,009
         For publication
    in newspapers worldwide.

1652
01:19:09,011 --> 01:19:11,312
     And millions of readers
          discovered it

1653
01:19:11,314 --> 01:19:13,447
          In the paper
      or in one his books,

1654
01:19:13,449 --> 01:19:16,183
      Where we all brought
   our individual experiences

1655
01:19:16,185 --> 01:19:19,920
        And perspectives
       into the equation.

1656
01:19:19,922 --> 01:19:25,159
 And bill watterson has repeated
    this process 3,160 times.

1657
01:19:25,161 --> 01:19:28,229
      Each of these strips
      holds the potential

1658
01:19:28,231 --> 01:19:33,100
   To touch someone somewhere
  in a unique and personal way.

1659
01:19:33,102 --> 01:19:37,972
   Many of watterson's strips
  mean something special to me.

1660
01:19:37,974 --> 01:19:40,441
     Some bring a huge smile
           to my face,

1661
01:19:40,443 --> 01:19:45,846
   Some challenge me to think,
 and a few are more melancholy.

1662
01:19:45,848 --> 01:19:49,416
  I see some strips differently
    now than I did as a kid.

1663
01:19:49,418 --> 01:19:51,252
    And for me, looking back,

1664
01:19:51,254 --> 01:19:55,790
     This strip foreshadows
 the end of "calvin and hobbes."

1665
01:20:17,412 --> 01:20:19,513
        -I just remember
        the announcement.

1666
01:20:19,515 --> 01:20:21,882
       I remember reading
        the final comic.

1667
01:20:21,884 --> 01:20:25,386
       I remember knowing
  that that was going to be it

1668
01:20:25,388 --> 01:20:30,324
         And that it was
 a really poignant way to end it

1669
01:20:30,326 --> 01:20:33,160
     And true to everything
    he'd built up before it.

1670
01:20:33,162 --> 01:20:35,563
     -I certainly remember
     opening the comic page

1671
01:20:35,565 --> 01:20:37,998
        That last Sunday
     in the <i>chicago tribune</i>

1672
01:20:38,000 --> 01:20:40,501
  And seeing it and being like,
        "wow. It's over."

1673
01:20:40,503 --> 01:20:43,270
    You just weren't used to
    comics ending, you know?

1674
01:20:43,272 --> 01:20:46,907
     Like, they kept going.
   That was part of the deal.

1675
01:20:46,909 --> 01:20:52,246
        -The final strip
       was the last draw.

1676
01:20:52,248 --> 01:20:56,317
   All the elements that made
 the strip wonderful were there,

1677
01:20:56,319 --> 01:21:00,421
      Including the drawing
 that was so much a part of it.

1678
01:21:00,423 --> 01:21:02,489
   There were very few words.

1679
01:21:02,491 --> 01:21:04,959
        -Everyone who was
    a "calvin and hobbes" fan

1680
01:21:04,961 --> 01:21:07,127
      Remembers two strips.

1681
01:21:07,129 --> 01:21:10,097
         One is that one
 that spoke to them individually

1682
01:21:10,099 --> 01:21:13,500
       And the last one --
      "let's go exploring!"

1683
01:21:13,502 --> 01:21:16,503
 And it was just a wonderful way
       for him to end it.

1684
01:21:16,505 --> 01:21:18,973
     -The way he handled it
        was so wonderful

1685
01:21:18,975 --> 01:21:21,075
         With, you know,
       the toboggan ride,

1686
01:21:21,077 --> 01:21:24,011
       Which was very much
     a staple of the strip,

1687
01:21:24,013 --> 01:21:26,881
 Going off into just wide-open.

1688
01:21:26,883 --> 01:21:29,617
     It wasn't nothingness,
          as I saw it.

1689
01:21:29,619 --> 01:21:32,319
     It was everything-ness.

1690
01:21:32,321 --> 01:21:34,922
     You know, white is not
     the absence of color.

1691
01:21:34,924 --> 01:21:36,891
      White is all colors.

1692
01:21:36,893 --> 01:21:40,227
       And you could make
       whatever you wanted

1693
01:21:40,229 --> 01:21:42,429
   Out of that final episode.

1694
01:21:42,431 --> 01:21:43,964
         And, honestly,

1695
01:21:43,966 --> 01:21:46,233
    How else is a cartoonist
    going to see the world?

1696
01:21:46,235 --> 01:21:48,435
          It has to be
     a big, wide-open world,

1697
01:21:48,437 --> 01:21:53,440
     Because until you draw
     your very last strip,

1698
01:21:53,442 --> 01:21:56,577
     You've got to come up
     with a brand-new story

1699
01:21:56,579 --> 01:21:59,580
        Out of that world
        every single day.

1700
01:21:59,582 --> 01:22:05,319
    -You know, it was an end
posed as a beginning, basically.

1701
01:22:05,321 --> 01:22:08,289
 -There's just something magical
  about that particular strip,

1702
01:22:08,291 --> 01:22:09,590
  Where, you know, it really is

1703
01:22:09,592 --> 01:22:11,492
    Just looking at the world
             afresh.

1704
01:22:11,494 --> 01:22:14,428
    I imagine that's what
    bill watterson must have
    felt like, you know,

1705
01:22:14,430 --> 01:22:16,297
        When he finished
       that last strip --

1706
01:22:16,299 --> 01:22:19,033
    "it's a magical world.
    Now I can move on.
    What's next in my life?"

1707
01:22:19,035 --> 01:22:20,634
   -He's trying to show us all

1708
01:22:20,636 --> 01:22:23,404
  That, you know, there's more
  to life than a comic strip,

1709
01:22:23,406 --> 01:22:25,039
            I think,

1710
01:22:25,041 --> 01:22:27,241
   And trying to make us feel
      a little bit better,

1711
01:22:27,243 --> 01:22:28,509
      But it doesn't work.

1712
01:22:28,511 --> 01:22:30,110
     It doesn't work at all.
          [ chuckles ]

1713
01:22:30,112 --> 01:22:31,679
     -It gave the impression

1714
01:22:31,681 --> 01:22:34,949
     That he was going to be
 exploring [laughs] new things,

1715
01:22:34,951 --> 01:22:37,217
       And he probably is
      exploring new things,

1716
01:22:37,219 --> 01:22:39,353
          But he's not
     sharing those publicly,

1717
01:22:39,355 --> 01:22:43,090
        And so [chuckles]
         that's too bad.

1718
01:22:43,092 --> 01:22:45,259
    -The final strip, for me,

1719
01:22:45,261 --> 01:22:48,195
   Is bittersweet in the sense
      that it was the end,

1720
01:22:48,197 --> 01:22:50,998
      But the thought that,
        at the end of it,

1721
01:22:51,000 --> 01:22:53,634
       You're being told,
      "let's go exploring,"

1722
01:22:53,636 --> 01:22:55,602
       Which is something
      I think watterson did

1723
01:22:55,604 --> 01:22:57,338
       Throughout his time
          in the strip,

1724
01:22:57,340 --> 01:22:59,373
   Whether it was making leaps
         in the artwork

1725
01:22:59,375 --> 01:23:01,308
   So you had to kind of think
       what was happening

1726
01:23:01,310 --> 01:23:03,644
    In the little white space
       between the panels,

1727
01:23:03,646 --> 01:23:05,279
   Or whether it was the fact

1728
01:23:05,281 --> 01:23:08,015
    That an adventure didn't
   necessarily end succinctly

1729
01:23:08,017 --> 01:23:09,216
      At the end of a strip

1730
01:23:09,218 --> 01:23:10,684
  So you had to kind of imagine

1731
01:23:10,686 --> 01:23:12,753
    What might have happened
           afterwards,

1732
01:23:12,755 --> 01:23:16,023
          He was always
 telling his readers to explore.

1733
01:23:16,025 --> 01:23:18,258
      -There is still magic
        in everyday life

1734
01:23:18,260 --> 01:23:19,660
   If you know where to look.

1735
01:23:19,662 --> 01:23:22,329
      And maybe if we look
      in the right place,

1736
01:23:22,331 --> 01:23:26,033
   There is something else as
wonderful as "calvin and hobbes"

1737
01:23:26,035 --> 01:23:29,703
 Or something that will give us
        that daily magic.

1738
01:23:29,705 --> 01:23:31,605
     But we have to find it.

1739
01:23:31,607 --> 01:23:34,641
    It may well be out there,
         as calvin said.

1740
01:23:34,643 --> 01:23:38,312
  It's up to us to look for it
       and to discover it.

1741
01:23:43,618 --> 01:23:47,588
 -There is that saying that all
good things must come to an end,

1742
01:23:47,590 --> 01:23:49,523
 But I'm not sure I believe it.

1743
01:23:49,525 --> 01:23:51,625
As long as there are new readers

1744
01:23:51,627 --> 01:23:54,261
        Being introduced
     to "calvin and hobbes,"

1745
01:23:54,263 --> 01:23:56,563
Watterson's legacy will live on.

1746
01:23:56,565 --> 01:23:58,599
And with those final three words

1747
01:23:58,601 --> 01:24:01,068
      That almost every fan
           can recite,

1748
01:24:01,070 --> 01:24:04,138
     So many new adventures
           will begin.

1749
01:29:14,782 --> 01:29:16,950
     -So here is a question
           for you --

1750
01:29:16,952 --> 01:29:20,454
    Have you guys or have you
 written a letter to watterson,

1751
01:29:20,456 --> 01:29:23,857
      And if so, you know,
  what was the experience like?

1752
01:29:23,859 --> 01:29:26,760
        -I never have --
not when I was younger, not now.

1753
01:29:26,762 --> 01:29:28,028
            -Mm-hmm.

1754
01:29:28,030 --> 01:29:31,631
       -I have a word file
         on my computer,

1755
01:29:31,633 --> 01:29:33,967
    And it's one line so far.

1756
01:29:33,969 --> 01:29:36,603
         All it says is,
      "dear mr. Watterson."

1757
01:29:36,605 --> 01:29:38,939
           -[ laughs ]
          very fitting.

1758
01:29:38,941 --> 01:29:41,074
     -There is nothing else.
     -Very fitting.

1759
01:29:41,076 --> 01:29:42,776
       -Not another word.

